var tafsirData_4 = {
  1: {
    "O humanity! Be mindful of your Lord": "This is a universal call to all human beings, not just Muslims. Allah is addressing every person who has ever lived or will ever live. Being 'mindful' (taqwa) means to be conscious of Allah, to fear displeasing Him, and to act with awareness that He sees everything you do. This is the foundation of all righteous behavior. When you truly remember that Allah is watching, you naturally avoid wrongdoing and strive to do good.",
    "Who created you from a single soul": "Allah reminds humanity of their common origin. All human beings—regardless of race, nationality, or social status—came from one person: Adam (peace be upon him). This is a powerful reminder that racism, tribalism, and feelings of superiority have no basis in Islam. The Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) said in his farewell sermon: 'All mankind is from Adam, and Adam was created from dust. An Arab has no superiority over a non-Arab, nor does a non-Arab have any superiority over an Arab.' This shared origin should create humility and brotherhood among all people.",
    "and from it He created its mate": "From Adam, Allah created his wife Hawwa (Eve). This shows that men and women share the same essence and origin. Neither gender is superior to the other in their humanity. They are partners meant to complement each other. The word 'mate' (zawj) implies companionship, comfort, and completion—marriage is meant to bring peace and tranquility.",
    "and through both He spread countless men and women": "From this original pair, Allah caused humanity to multiply and spread across the earth. Every single human being is connected through this lineage. This reminds us that harming another person is like harming your own extended family. The diversity of nations and peoples all trace back to this single origin.",
    "And be mindful of Allah—in Whose Name you appeal to one another": "People often invoke Allah's name when making requests or agreements, saying things like 'I ask you by Allah' or 'For Allah's sake, help me.' This verse reminds us to honor the sanctity of such appeals. When someone asks you in Allah's name, take it seriously. More importantly, be conscious of Allah in all your dealings with others.",
    "and ˹honour˺ family ties": "Maintaining family relationships (silat al-rahm) is a major obligation in Islam. The Arabic word for 'womb' (rahm) is derived from Allah's name Ar-Rahman (The Most Merciful). The Prophet (peace be upon him) said that Allah said: 'I am Ar-Rahman, and I created the womb (rahm) and derived its name from My name. Whoever maintains family ties, I will maintain connection with him, and whoever severs family ties, I will sever connection with him.' This includes parents, siblings, uncles, aunts, cousins, and all relatives—even if they are difficult to deal with.",
    "Surely Allah is ever Watchful over you": "This is both a warning and a comfort. Allah sees everything—your actions, your intentions, how you treat your relatives, how you deal with others. Nothing escapes His knowledge. For the righteous, this is reassuring because Allah will reward their good deeds. For those who wrong others, this is a warning that they will be held accountable."
  },
  2: {
    "Give orphans their wealth ˹when they reach maturity˺": "An orphan in Islamic terminology is a child who has lost their father before reaching puberty. When orphans grow up and become mature adults capable of managing their affairs, their guardians must hand over their property completely and honestly. This was revealed because some guardians in pre-Islamic Arabia would keep orphans' wealth for themselves, leaving the orphans with nothing when they grew up. Islam came to protect the vulnerable.",
    "and do not exchange your worthless possessions for their valuables": "Some dishonest guardians would swap their own low-quality items (like sick animals or damaged goods) for the orphan's high-quality possessions (like healthy livestock or valuable property). This verse forbids such fraudulent exchanges. Even if the items appear similar on the surface, taking advantage of an orphan's inability to protect their interests is strictly forbidden.",
    "nor cheat them by mixing their wealth with your own": "Another deceptive practice was to mix the orphan's money or property with one's own, making it impossible to distinguish between them. Then the guardian would claim everything belonged to them. This verse prohibits any scheme designed to unlawfully consume an orphan's wealth.",
    "For this would indeed be a great sin": "Stealing from orphans is not a minor mistake—it is among the major sins in Islam. The Prophet (peace be upon him) listed 'consuming the wealth of orphans' among the seven destructive sins that a Muslim must avoid. Orphans have already lost their protector (their father); taking advantage of their vulnerability compounds the injustice."
  },
  3: {
    "If you fear you might fail to give orphan women their ˹due˺ rights ˹if you were to marry them˺": "This verse was revealed to address a specific problem. Some guardians would marry the orphan girls under their care to gain control of their wealth, but then mistreat them or refuse to give them their proper dowry. Aisha (may Allah be pleased with her) explained that this verse addressed men who wanted to marry orphan women for their beauty or wealth but were unwilling to give them fair treatment.",
    "then marry other women of your choice—two, three, or four": "If you cannot be just to orphan women, then leave them alone and marry other women instead. This verse permits polygamy (up to four wives) but frames it within the context of justice. The permission is not unlimited—it comes with strict conditions.",
    "But if you are afraid you will fail to maintain justice, then ˹content yourselves with˺ one": "Justice between wives includes equal time, equal financial support, and equal treatment in all material matters. If a man doubts his ability to be fair, he must limit himself to one wife. The Quran itself later states: 'You will never be able to be completely fair between wives, even if you try' (4:129), indicating that complete emotional equality is impossible, but material fairness is required.",
    "or those ˹bondwomen˺ in your possession": "This refers to the historical context where captives from war could become part of a household. Islam regulated this existing practice with rights and protections, and the overall direction of Islamic teachings encouraged freeing such individuals.",
    "This way you are less likely to commit injustice": "The purpose of these restrictions is to prevent oppression. Marriage should bring comfort and stability, not become a means of exploiting women. By limiting the number of wives and emphasizing justice, Islam protects women's rights."
  },
  4: {
    "Give women ˹you wed˺ their due dowries graciously": "The dowry (mahr) is the wife's absolute right. It is a gift from the husband to the wife, and it becomes her property alone. The husband has no right to take it back or control how she uses it. The word 'graciously' (nihlah) means it should be given willingly, happily, and without resentment—not as a burden but as an honor.",
    "But if they waive some of it willingly, then you may enjoy it freely with a clear conscience": "If a wife, of her own free choice and without pressure, decides to give back part or all of her dowry to her husband, he may accept it. The key word is 'willingly'—there must be no coercion, manipulation, or family pressure. This shows Islam's respect for women's autonomy over their own property."
  },
  5: {
    "Do not entrust the incapable ˹among your dependants˺ with your wealth which Allah has made a means of support for you": "Some people—whether due to mental incapacity, extreme youth, or poor judgment—are not able to manage money responsibly. Giving them direct control over significant wealth could lead to its loss, harming both them and others who depend on that wealth. This verse instructs guardians to manage such wealth responsibly rather than handing it over to those who would waste it.",
    "but feed and clothe them from it": "Even though they don't control the wealth directly, their needs must be fully met. They should not be deprived of food, clothing, shelter, or any necessities. The wealth should serve them even if they don't manage it themselves.",
    "and speak to them kindly": "People who cannot manage their own affairs often feel frustrated, embarrassed, or inferior. Islam commands that they be treated with dignity and kindness. Harsh words, mockery, or condescension are forbidden. Their human dignity must be preserved even when their financial independence is limited."
  },
  6: {
    "Test ˹the competence of˺ the orphans until they reach a marriageable age": "Before handing over an orphan's wealth, the guardian must verify that the orphan is mature enough to handle it responsibly. This testing involves observing their decision-making abilities, giving them small amounts to manage, and seeing how they handle financial matters. The 'marriageable age' refers to physical and mental maturity—when they can understand contracts, marriage, and financial responsibilities.",
    "Then if you feel they are capable of sound judgment, return their wealth to them": "Maturity alone is not enough; the orphan must also demonstrate rushd—sound judgment and the ability to manage money wisely. If a young person reaches adulthood but still makes foolish financial decisions, the guardian may delay handing over the wealth until they develop better judgment. This protects the orphan from their own inexperience.",
    "And do not consume it wastefully and hastily before they grow up ˹to demand it˺": "Some guardians would rush to spend the orphan's wealth while they were still young, fearing that once the orphan grew up, they would demand an accounting. This verse forbids such behavior. The guardian must preserve the wealth, not deplete it.",
    "If the guardian is well-off, they should not take compensation": "A wealthy guardian should serve the orphan without taking any payment from the orphan's wealth. This is an act of charity and righteousness that will be rewarded by Allah.",
    "but if the guardian is poor, let them take a reasonable provision": "Islam is practical. If a guardian is poor and spends their time and effort managing an orphan's affairs, they may take a fair and modest amount as compensation for their work—not as profit, but as reasonable payment for their labor.",
    "When you give orphans back their property, call in witnesses": "To protect both the guardian and the orphan from future disputes, the handover should be documented with witnesses. This prevents the orphan from later claiming they received less than they were owed, and it protects the guardian from false accusations.",
    "And sufficient is Allah as a ˹vigilant˺ Reckoner": "Even if no human witnesses are present, Allah sees everything. He keeps perfect accounts of every transaction. This is a reminder that even if someone cheats an orphan and gets away with it in this world, Allah will hold them accountable on the Day of Judgment."
  },
  7: {
    "For men there is a share in what their parents and close relatives leave": "Islam establishes that men have a God-given right to inherit from their deceased relatives. This was significant because some cultures excluded certain family members from inheritance entirely.",
    "and for women there is a share in what their parents and close relatives leave": "This was revolutionary. In pre-Islamic Arabia, women often received nothing from inheritance—sometimes they themselves were inherited as property! Islam firmly established women's right to inherit, making it a divine law that cannot be denied.",
    "whether it is little or much": "The inheritance laws apply regardless of the size of the estate. Whether the deceased left behind vast wealth or modest possessions, the shares must be distributed according to Allah's law.",
    "˹These are˺ obligatory shares": "These are not suggestions or recommendations—they are mandatory. No one has the right to deprive an heir of their share or to alter Allah's prescribed distribution."
  },
  8: {
    "If ˹non-inheriting˺ relatives, orphans, or the needy are present at the time of distribution": "When the inheritance is being divided, there may be people present who are not entitled to a legal share—perhaps distant relatives, orphans from the community, or poor people.",
    "offer them a ˹small˺ provision from it": "Out of kindness and generosity, give them something from the estate before the formal distribution. This is an act of charity that brings blessings and maintains social bonds.",
    "and speak to them kindly": "If you cannot give them anything (perhaps because the estate is small), at least speak to them with kindness and respect. Don't make them feel embarrassed for being present or for their need."
  },
  9: {
    "Let the guardians be as concerned ˹for the orphans˺ as they would if they were to ˹die and˺ leave ˹their own˺ helpless children behind": "This verse appeals to human empathy. Imagine if you died and left behind young children—how would you want others to treat them? You would want people to be kind, honest, and protective of your children's rights and property. Treat orphans under your care with the same concern and compassion you would want for your own children if they became orphans.",
    "So let them be mindful of Allah": "Acting justly toward orphans is ultimately about fearing Allah. Human supervision may fail, but Allah's supervision never does.",
    "and speak equitably": "Even the words spoken to orphans matter. Guardians should not speak harshly, mockingly, or dismissively to orphans. They deserve kind, respectful, and fair speech that preserves their dignity."
  },
  10: {
    "Indeed, those who unjustly consume orphans' wealth": "This refers to anyone who takes what belongs to an orphan without right—whether through theft, fraud, or mismanagement.",
    "˹in fact˺ consume nothing but fire into their bellies": "This is a vivid and terrifying image. What they eat from the orphan's wealth is not nourishment—it is fire that will burn them from within. The Quran uses this imagery to show that ill-gotten wealth brings no benefit; it only brings destruction.",
    "And they will be burned in a blazing Hell": "The punishment continues in the Hereafter. Those who wronged orphans will face the Fire of Hell. This severe warning shows how seriously Allah takes the protection of vulnerable members of society."
  },
  11: {
    "Allah commands you regarding your children: the share of the male will be twice that of the female": "This is Allah's command, not a human decision that can be debated. The male receives double the female's share in this specific situation. This is because Islamic law requires men to financially support their wives, children, and other dependents, while women's earnings and inheritance are entirely their own. A woman keeps her inheritance for herself; a man must spend his on his family. When these responsibilities are considered, the system is balanced.",
    "If you leave only two ˹or more˺ females, their share is two-thirds of the estate": "When the deceased has only daughters (two or more) and no sons, the daughters together receive two-thirds of the estate.",
    "But if there is only one female, her share will be one-half": "A single daughter receives half of the estate.",
    "Each parent is entitled to one-sixth if you leave offspring": "If the deceased has children, each of their parents (the deceased's father and mother) receives one-sixth of the estate.",
    "But if you are childless and your parents are the only heirs, then your mother will receive one-third": "If someone dies without children and only their parents inherit, the mother receives one-third and the father receives the remaining two-thirds.",
    "But if you leave siblings, then your mother will receive one-sixth": "If the deceased has siblings (even if they don't inherit), the mother's share is reduced to one-sixth because the father will need to support those siblings.",
    "after the fulfilment of bequests and debts": "Before any inheritance is distributed, two things must be settled first: (1) any debts the deceased owed must be paid, and (2) any bequests (wasiyyah) the deceased made (up to one-third of the estate for non-heirs) must be fulfilled.",
    "˹Be fair to˺ your parents and children, as you do not ˹fully˺ know who is more beneficial to you": "You might think your children will benefit you more than your parents, or vice versa. But only Allah knows the unseen. Perhaps your parents' prayers for you are more valuable than your children's help. Trust Allah's distribution.",
    "˹This is˺ an obligation from Allah. Surely Allah is All-Knowing, All-Wise": "These laws come from the One who knows everything and whose wisdom is perfect. Even if humans don't fully understand the reasoning, they should trust that Allah's system is the most just and beneficial."
  },
  12: {
    "You will inherit half of what your wives leave if they are childless": "A husband inherits half of his deceased wife's estate if she had no children.",
    "But if they have children, then ˹your share is˺ one-fourth of the estate": "If the wife had children (whether from this husband or a previous marriage), the husband's share is reduced to one-fourth.",
    "after the fulfilment of bequests and debts": "The same principle applies—settle obligations first.",
    "And your wives will inherit one-fourth of what you leave if you are childless": "A wife inherits one-fourth of her deceased husband's estate if he had no children.",
    "But if you have children, then your wives will receive one-eighth of your estate": "If the husband had children, the wife's share is one-eighth. If there are multiple wives, they share this one-eighth among themselves.",
    "And if a man or a woman leaves neither parents nor children but only a brother or a sister ˹from their mother's side˺, they will each inherit one-sixth": "This addresses the case of someone who dies with no parents and no children (called kalalah). If they have maternal half-siblings (siblings from the same mother but different fathers), each sibling gets one-sixth.",
    "but if they are more than one, they ˹all˺ will share one-third of the estate": "If there are multiple maternal half-siblings, they share one-third equally among themselves, regardless of gender.",
    "after the fulfilment of bequests and debts without harm ˹to the heirs˺": "Bequests and debts must not be used to harm the rightful heirs. For example, someone cannot make a bequest specifically designed to deprive their heirs of their shares or falsely claim debts.",
    "˹This is˺ a commandment from Allah. And Allah is All-Knowing, Most Forbearing": "Allah knows all circumstances and is patient with human weaknesses, but His laws must be followed."
  },
  13: {
    "These ˹entitlements˺ are the limits set by Allah": "The inheritance shares are divine boundaries that must not be crossed. They are not suggestions but fixed laws.",
    "Whoever obeys Allah and His Messenger will be admitted into Gardens under which rivers flow": "Those who follow these laws—respecting the rights of heirs and distributing wealth justly—will be rewarded with Paradise.",
    "to stay there forever. That is the ultimate triumph": "The reward is eternal, not temporary. This is the greatest success anyone can achieve."
  },
  14: {
    "But whoever disobeys Allah and His Messenger and exceeds their limits": "Those who violate the inheritance laws—taking more than their share, depriving others of their rights, or manipulating the system—are transgressors.",
    "will be cast into Hell, to stay there forever": "The punishment for such disobedience, if one considers it permissible to violate Allah's laws, is eternal Hellfire.",
    "And they will suffer a humiliating punishment": "Beyond the physical torment, there will be shame and disgrace. Those who stole from the weak and vulnerable will be humiliated before all of creation."
  },
  15: {
    "˹As for˺ those of your women who commit illegal intercourse": "This refers to sexual relations outside of marriage (zina), which is a major sin in Islam that destroys families, spreads disease, confuses lineage, and corrupts society.",
    "call four witnesses from among yourselves": "To prove such a serious accusation, four trustworthy male witnesses must testify that they directly witnessed the act. This extremely high standard of proof protects people from false accusations and slander. In practice, this means the act must have been committed openly and brazenly.",
    "If they testify, confine the offenders to their homes until they die or Allah ordains a ˹different˺ way for them": "This was an early ruling that was later replaced (abrogated) by the punishment specified in Surah An-Nur (24:2)—one hundred lashes for unmarried offenders. For married offenders, the punishment established by the Prophet's practice is stoning. The phrase 'or Allah ordains a different way' indicated that a more specific ruling would come later."
  },
  16: {
    "And the two among you who commit this sin—discipline them": "Both parties involved in the sin should face consequences. The 'discipline' mentioned here was later specified through subsequent revelations and prophetic guidance.",
    "If they repent and mend their ways, relieve them": "If the offenders sincerely repent and correct their behavior, they should not be continually punished or socially ostracized. Islam believes in rehabilitation and giving people the chance to change.",
    "Surely Allah is ever Accepting of Repentance, Most Merciful": "Allah's mercy is vast. No matter how great the sin, sincere repentance can erase it. Allah loves to forgive those who turn back to Him."
  },
  17: {
    "Allah only accepts the repentance of those who commit evil ignorantly ˹or recklessly˺": "'Ignorantly' here doesn't mean they didn't know it was wrong, but rather that they acted impulsively, driven by desire, without fully considering the consequences. Every sin involves a degree of 'ignorance' in the sense that the person ignores Allah's warning at the moment of sinning.",
    "then repent soon after": "The repentance should come quickly—before death approaches. 'Soon' means not delaying repentance indefinitely, thinking one can sin now and repent later. The scholars say as long as the soul has not reached the throat (the moment of death), repentance is still possible.",
    "Allah will pardon them. And Allah is All-Knowing, All-Wise": "Allah knows who is sincere and who is merely pretending. His wisdom determines how He deals with each person's repentance."
  },
  18: {
    "However, repentance is not accepted from those who knowingly persist in sin until they start dying, and then cry, 'Now I repent!'": "Some people deliberately continue sinning, planning to repent at the last moment before death. But when death actually comes, their 'repentance' is worthless. Pharaoh tried this—when he was drowning, he suddenly declared faith, but it was too late. True repentance requires time to prove its sincerity through changed behavior.",
    "nor those who die as disbelievers": "Those who reject faith entirely and die in that state cannot benefit from repentance. The opportunity for repentance ends at death.",
    "For them We have prepared a painful punishment": "Both groups—those who delay repentance until death and those who die as disbelievers—face severe punishment in the Hereafter."
  },
  19: {
    "O believers! It is not permissible for you to inherit women against their will": "In pre-Islamic Arabia, when a man died, his male relatives would sometimes 'inherit' his widow as part of his estate. They might marry her themselves without her consent or prevent her from remarrying so they could keep her dowry. Islam abolished this cruel practice entirely. Women are human beings with rights, not property to be inherited.",
    "or mistreat them to make them return some of the dowry ˹as a ransom for divorce˺": "Some men would treat their wives so badly that the women would give back their dowry just to escape the marriage (this is called khul'). Using cruelty as a tool to recover the dowry is absolutely forbidden.",
    "unless they are found guilty of adultery": "The only exception is if the wife commits clear, proven adultery. In such a case, different rules may apply regarding the dowry.",
    "Treat them fairly": "Even if you don't love your wife, you must still treat her with fairness and respect. Islam commands good treatment regardless of personal feelings.",
    "If you happen to dislike them, you may hate something which Allah turns into a great blessing": "A marriage you find difficult might produce righteous children, bring unexpected blessings, or teach you patience. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said: 'A believing man should not hate a believing woman. If he dislikes one of her characteristics, he will be pleased with another.' Don't make hasty decisions based on temporary feelings."
  },
  20: {
    "If you desire to replace a wife with another": "If a man decides to divorce one wife and marry another, he must still treat the first wife justly.",
    "and you have given the former ˹even˺ a stack of gold ˹as a dowry˺": "Even if the dowry was enormous—a 'qintar' (a massive amount) of gold—it belongs to her.",
    "do not take any of it back": "The dowry, once given, is the wife's property forever. Divorce does not give the husband any right to reclaim it.",
    "Would you ˹still˺ take it unjustly and very sinfully?": "This rhetorical question emphasizes how wrong it would be. Taking back the dowry combines injustice (wronging another person) with sin (violating Allah's command)."
  },
  21: {
    "And how could you take it back after having enjoyed each other intimately": "Marriage involves the most personal and intimate relationship between two people. After sharing such closeness, how could a man justify taking back what he gave her?",
    "and she has taken from you a firm commitment?": "Marriage in Islam is described as a 'mithaq ghalith'—a solemn, firm covenant. It's not a casual arrangement but a sacred contract witnessed by Allah. This emphasizes the seriousness of marriage and the weight of the commitments made."
  },
  22: {
    "Do not marry former wives of your fathers": "Marrying a woman who was married to your father is absolutely forbidden in Islam. This includes your biological father, and scholars extend it to grandfathers as well. Such a marriage would be considered incestuous and would violate the honor and structure of the family.",
    "except what was done previously": "Those who had such marriages before Islam are not punished for what happened in ignorance, but they must end such relationships after accepting Islam.",
    "It was indeed a shameful, despicable, and evil practice": "Three words are used to condemn this practice: (1) 'shameful' (fahishah)—morally outrageous; (2) 'despicable' (maqt)—hateful and disgusting; (3) 'evil' (sa'a sabila)—a terrible path. This strong language leaves no doubt about how seriously Islam views this prohibition."
  },
  23: {
    "˹Also˺ forbidden to you for marriage are your mothers, your daughters, your sisters": "These are permanently forbidden due to direct blood relationships. 'Mothers' includes grandmothers, 'daughters' includes granddaughters, and 'sisters' includes both full sisters and half-sisters.",
    "your paternal and maternal aunts": "Sisters of your father and sisters of your mother, and their preceding generations, are all forbidden.",
    "your brother's daughters, your sister's daughters": "Nieces from both brothers and sisters are forbidden, including their descendants.",
    "your foster-mothers": "Women who breastfed you during infancy become like mothers to you. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said: 'What becomes forbidden through breastfeeding is the same as what becomes forbidden through blood relationships.'",
    "your foster-sisters": "Girls who were breastfed by the same woman who breastfed you are like sisters to you.",
    "your mothers-in-law": "The moment you marry a woman, her mother becomes permanently forbidden to you, even if you later divorce her daughter.",
    "your stepdaughters under your guardianship if you have consummated marriage with their mothers—but if you have not, then you can marry them": "If you marry a woman who has a daughter from a previous marriage, that daughter becomes forbidden to you—but only if you consummated the marriage with her mother. If you divorced the mother before consummation, the daughter is not forbidden.",
    "nor the wives of your own sons": "The wives of your biological sons are permanently forbidden. This does not include adopted sons, as Islam does not recognize adoption in the sense of changing lineage.",
    "nor two sisters together at the same time": "You cannot be married to two sisters simultaneously. If one dies or you divorce her (and her waiting period ends), you can marry her sister.",
    "except what was done previously": "Previous marriages that violated these rules before one knew the law are forgiven.",
    "Surely Allah is All-Forgiving, Most Merciful": "Allah forgives past mistakes made in ignorance and shows mercy to those who repent and correct their ways."
  },
  24: {
    "Also ˹forbidden are˺ married women—except ˹female˺ captives in your possession": "A woman who is already married to someone else is forbidden. The exception refers to the historical context of captives from war whose previous marriages were dissolved by their captivity.",
    "This is Allah's commandment to you": "These prohibitions are divine law, not human customs that can be changed.",
    "˹But˺ lawful to you are all beyond these": "Any woman not mentioned in the prohibited categories is potentially lawful for marriage.",
    "as long as you seek them with your wealth in a legal marriage, not in fornication": "Marriage must be conducted properly—with a dowry, witnesses, and consent. Illicit relationships are forbidden.",
    "Give those you have consummated marriage with their due dowries": "The dowry becomes obligatory after consummation of the marriage.",
    "It is permissible to be mutually gracious regarding the set dowry": "If both parties agree to adjust the dowry—whether the wife forgives some of it or the husband gives more—that is permissible.",
    "Surely Allah is All-Knowing, All-Wise": "Allah's laws are based on perfect knowledge and wisdom, designed for human benefit."
  },
  25: {
    "But if any of you cannot afford to marry a free believing woman, then ˹let him marry˺ a believing bondwoman possessed by one of you": "This verse addresses the historical reality of slavery and provides guidance for those who could not afford the dowry required to marry a free woman. Marrying a believing bondwoman was presented as an option, though marrying a free woman was preferable.",
    "Allah knows best ˹the state of˺ your faith ˹and theirs˺": "Don't look down on bondwomen. Allah knows their true faith, which might be stronger than that of free women. External status doesn't determine spiritual worth.",
    "You are from one another": "Free people and bondspeople are all human beings, all from Adam. There should be no arrogance based on social status.",
    "So marry them with the permission of their owners, giving them their dowry in fairness": "Even bondwomen have the right to a proper marriage contract and dowry. Their owners must consent to the marriage, and the dowry must be fair.",
    "if they are chaste, neither promiscuous nor having secret affairs": "The bondwomen should be of good character—not engaging in open immorality or secret relationships.",
    "If they commit indecency after marriage, they receive half the punishment of free women": "Because bondwomen had less social protection and education, their punishment for certain offenses was half that of free women. This shows consideration for circumstances.",
    "This is for those of you who fear falling into sin": "This permission to marry bondwomen is for those who genuinely struggle to remain chaste and cannot afford to marry free women.",
    "But if you are patient, it is better for you": "Patience—waiting until one can afford to marry a free woman—is described as better. The permission to marry bondwomen was a concession, not the ideal.",
    "And Allah is All-Forgiving, Most Merciful": "Allah understands human weakness and provides lawful outlets while forgiving those who struggle."
  },
  26: {
    "It is Allah's Will to make things clear to you": "Allah does not leave humanity in confusion. He explains His laws clearly so people know exactly what is permitted and forbidden.",
    "guide you to the ˹noble˺ ways of those before you": "The moral path Islam teaches is the same path followed by righteous people throughout history—prophets, saints, and the sincere believers of previous nations.",
    "and turn to you in mercy": "Allah wants to forgive you and bring you back to Him. His intention is mercy, not punishment.",
    "For Allah is All-Knowing, All-Wise": "Allah's guidance is based on complete knowledge of human nature and perfect wisdom about what benefits humanity."
  },
  27: {
    "And it is Allah's Will to turn to you in grace": "Allah actively wants to show you favor, forgive your sins, and guide you to success.",
    "but those who follow their desires wish to see you deviate entirely ˹from Allah's Way˺": "People who are slaves to their desires want you to join them in sin. Misery loves company. They try to normalize immorality and make following Allah's guidance seem restrictive or outdated."
  },
  28: {
    "And it is Allah's Will to lighten your burdens": "Islam is meant to make life easier, not harder. The rules exist to protect people, not to burden them unnecessarily. When there is hardship, there is usually a concession.",
    "for humankind was created weak": "Humans are inherently weak—weak in resisting temptation, weak in patience, weak in physical endurance. Allah knows this and designs His laws accordingly. This verse should inspire humility, not excuse sin. We are weak, so we need Allah's help and guidance even more."
  },
  29: {
    "O believers! Do not devour one another's wealth illegally": "This comprehensive prohibition covers all forms of unlawful financial gain: theft, fraud, bribery, usury (interest), gambling, cheating in business, breaking contracts, and any other means of taking what doesn't belong to you.",
    "but rather trade by mutual consent": "Lawful trade requires both parties to agree willingly, with full knowledge of what they're getting. No deception, no coercion, no hidden defects. This principle establishes the foundation of ethical commerce.",
    "And do not kill ˹each other or˺ yourselves": "This prohibition covers both murder and suicide. Killing another person unjustly is one of the greatest sins. Killing yourself is also forbidden—your life belongs to Allah, not to you. The scholars also extend this to anything that gradually destroys your health, like harmful substances.",
    "Surely Allah is ever Merciful to you": "These prohibitions come from Allah's mercy, not His desire to restrict you. They protect life, property, and society."
  },
  30: {
    "And whoever does this sinfully and unjustly": "Whoever violates these commands—whether by taking others' wealth illegally or taking life—and does so deliberately with full knowledge that it is wrong...",
    "We will burn them in the Fire": "The punishment is Hellfire. Allah does not make empty threats.",
    "That is easy for Allah": "Executing this punishment is effortless for Allah. He is not limited in His power. Those who think they can escape accountability are deluding themselves."
  },
  31: {
    "If you avoid the major sins forbidden to you": "Major sins (kaba'ir) include things like shirk (associating partners with Allah), murder, adultery, consuming interest (riba), stealing, false testimony, and other serious transgressions specifically warned against in the Quran and Sunnah.",
    "We will absolve you of your ˹lesser˺ misdeeds": "This is a beautiful promise. If you stay away from the major sins, Allah will forgive your minor sins. Regular prayers, fasting, charity, and other good deeds also erase minor sins. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said: 'The five daily prayers and Friday prayer to the next Friday prayer are expiation for whatever sins come in between, so long as one avoids major sins.'",
    "and admit you into a place of honour": "The reward for avoiding major sins is not just forgiveness but an honorable entrance into Paradise. This 'place of honor' (mudkhal kareem) suggests dignity, respect, and a noble position in the Hereafter."
  },
  32: {
    "And do not crave what Allah has given some of you over others": "This verse addresses the natural human tendency toward envy and jealousy. Allah distributes His blessings differently among people—some have more wealth, others have better health, some have more children, others have greater knowledge. Instead of wishing you had what others have, accept what Allah has given you. Envy (hasad) is destructive; it burns the heart and leads to ingratitude. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said: 'Beware of envy, for envy consumes good deeds just as fire consumes wood.' This also applies to differences between men and women—each has been given different roles and responsibilities, and neither should wish to be the other.",
    "Men will be rewarded according to their deeds and women ˹equally˺ according to theirs": "Both men and women earn rewards based on their own actions. Allah judges people by their deeds, not their gender. A woman's good deeds are rewarded just as a man's are. This verse establishes complete spiritual equality before Allah while acknowledging that men and women may have different roles in society.",
    "Rather, ask Allah for His bounties": "Instead of envying others, turn to Allah and ask Him to bless you from His infinite treasures. Du'a (supplication) is the weapon of the believer. Allah's bounties are unlimited—when He gives to one person, it doesn't diminish what He can give to others. So ask Allah directly rather than coveting what He has given others.",
    "Surely Allah has ˹perfect˺ knowledge of all things": "Allah knows exactly what each person needs and what is best for them. Sometimes what appears to be a blessing is actually a test, and what seems like deprivation is actually protection. Trust Allah's wisdom in His distribution."
  },
  33: {
    "And We have appointed heirs to what has been left by parents and next of kin": "Allah has established a system of inheritance that ensures wealth passes to rightful heirs—children, parents, spouses, and other relatives. No one can arbitrarily decide to exclude a rightful heir or change the shares Allah has prescribed.",
    "As for those you have made a pledge to, give them their share": "In early Islam, some people had made pacts of mutual support and inheritance with non-relatives. This verse instructs that such pledges should be honored. Some scholars say this was later abrogated when the full inheritance laws were revealed, while others say it refers to bequests (wasiyyah) that can be made to non-heirs up to one-third of the estate.",
    "Surely Allah is a Witness over all things": "Allah sees every agreement made, every promise kept or broken, and every right fulfilled or violated. Nothing escapes His knowledge, so fulfill your obligations knowing you are being watched."
  },
  34: {
    "Men are the caretakers of women": "The Arabic word 'qawwamun' means protectors, maintainers, and those responsible for leadership. This does not mean dictators or oppressors—it means men bear the primary responsibility for providing for, protecting, and caring for their families. With this authority comes accountability before Allah. A leader who abuses his position will be questioned on the Day of Judgment.",
    "as men have been provisioned by Allah over women and tasked with supporting them financially": "Two reasons are given for male leadership: (1) Allah has given men certain qualities that suit them for this role, and (2) men are obligated to spend their wealth on their families. A woman's earnings belong entirely to her; a man's earnings must support his wife and children. This financial obligation is the basis of his authority.",
    "And righteous women are devoutly obedient and, when alone, protective of what Allah has entrusted them with": "Righteous wives are characterized by two qualities: (1) they are obedient—cooperating with their husbands in what is good (not in sin), and (2) they guard their chastity, their husband's honor, his wealth, and his secrets when he is absent. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said the best women are those who please their husbands when they look at them, obey them when they command them (in good), and do not go against their wishes regarding themselves or their wealth.",
    "And if you sense ill-conduct from your women, advise them ˹first˺": "Nushuz (ill-conduct) refers to a wife's rebellion against her husband—arrogance, refusal to fulfill her duties, or defiance. The first step is gentle advice, reminding her of Allah and her responsibilities. Most problems can be solved through calm, loving communication.",
    "˹if they persist,˺ do not share their beds": "If advice doesn't work, the husband may express his displeasure by sleeping separately. This is not abandoning the home but turning away in bed. This shows the seriousness of the situation without resorting to harsh measures.",
    "˹but if they still persist,˺ then discipline them ˹gently˺": "This is the last resort after the previous two steps have failed. The Prophet (peace be upon him) explained this must be light—not hitting the face, not causing injury, and not leaving marks. He also said: 'The best of you are those who are best to their wives, and I am the best of you to my wives.' Many scholars emphasize this should be symbolic at most, and the Prophet himself never struck any of his wives. He said: 'Do not strike the female servants of Allah.'",
    "But if they change their ways, do not be unjust to them": "Once the wife returns to good conduct, the husband must not hold grudges, bring up past issues, or continue punishing her. Forgiveness and moving forward is required.",
    "Surely Allah is Most High, All-Great": "This reminder of Allah's supreme power is a warning to husbands: do not abuse your authority, for there is One far greater than you who sees everything and will hold you accountable for how you treat your wife."
  },
  35: {
    "If you anticipate a split between them, appoint a mediator from his family and another from hers": "When marital problems become serious and the couple cannot resolve them alone, the community should intervene through family mediation. Each side sends a trustworthy, wise representative who knows the couple and can advocate for reconciliation while understanding each person's perspective.",
    "If they desire reconciliation, Allah will restore harmony between them": "The key is sincere intention. If both spouses genuinely want to save the marriage, Allah will help them find a way. But if one or both are stubborn or have already decided to separate, even the best mediators cannot help. Reconciliation requires both parties to want it.",
    "Surely Allah is All-Knowing, All-Aware": "Allah knows the true intentions in each person's heart—whether they sincerely want reconciliation or are just going through the motions. He is aware of every detail of the marital situation, even what neither spouse has expressed."
  },
  36: {
    "Worship Allah ˹alone˺ and associate none with Him": "This is the foundation of Islam—Tawhid (monotheism). All worship must be directed exclusively to Allah. No partners, no intermediaries, no idols. This is the first and greatest commandment, the purpose for which humans were created.",
    "And be kind to parents": "Immediately after mentioning His rights, Allah mentions parents' rights. This shows how important honoring parents is in Islam. The Prophet (peace be upon him) was asked: 'Which deed is most beloved to Allah?' He said: 'Prayer at its proper time.' He was asked: 'Then what?' He said: 'Kindness to parents.'",
    "relatives": "Extended family members deserve kindness, support, and maintaining ties with them—even those who are difficult or who cut ties with you.",
    "orphans": "Children who have lost their fathers are vulnerable and need the community's care, support, and protection.",
    "the poor": "Those who cannot meet their basic needs deserve charity and assistance from those whom Allah has blessed with wealth.",
    "near and distant neighbours": "The Prophet (peace be upon him) said: 'Jibril kept recommending that I treat neighbors well until I thought he would make them heirs.' A 'near neighbor' could mean one who lives close by or one who is a relative; a 'distant neighbor' could mean one who lives further away or is not related. Both deserve good treatment.",
    "close friends": "Companions, colleagues, travel partners—anyone you spend time with deserves good treatment. This includes coworkers, classmates, and anyone in your company.",
    "˹needy˺ travellers": "Travelers who are stranded or in need deserve hospitality and assistance, even if they are wealthy at home. Travel makes people vulnerable.",
    "and those ˹bondspeople˺ in your possession": "Even those in the lowest social positions must be treated with kindness. Islam improved the conditions of enslaved people and encouraged their freedom.",
    "Surely Allah does not like whoever is arrogant, boastful": "After listing all these social obligations, Allah warns against the opposite attitude—arrogance and boasting. Those who think they are better than others, who show off their blessings and look down on the poor, orphans, and vulnerable—Allah does not love them."
  },
  37: {
    "those who are stingy, promote stinginess among people": "Bad enough to be stingy yourself, but these people also encourage others to be stingy. They advise against charity, mock those who give, and spread a culture of hoarding rather than generosity.",
    "and withhold Allah's bounties": "They hide the blessings Allah has given them—whether wealth, knowledge, or other gifts—refusing to share or benefit others. This includes scholars who hide beneficial knowledge and wealthy people who refuse to give charity.",
    "We have prepared for the disbelievers a humiliating punishment": "Extreme stinginess and ingratitude can be signs of disbelief. Those who refuse to acknowledge Allah's blessings or fulfill their obligations face a humiliating punishment—appropriate for those whose arrogance prevented them from giving."
  },
  38: {
    "Likewise for those who spend their wealth to show off": "Spending for show (riya') destroys the reward of charity. These people give money, but their intention is to be praised by others, to gain reputation, or to show off their wealth—not to please Allah or help the needy.",
    "and do not believe in Allah or the Last Day": "Their showing off stems from not truly believing. If they believed in Allah, they would seek His pleasure alone. If they believed in the Last Day, they would know that only sincere deeds will be rewarded.",
    "And whoever takes Satan as an associate—what an evil associate they have!": "Satan encourages showing off and corrupts sincere intentions. Those who follow his whispers and make him their companion will find he leads them only to destruction. On the Day of Judgment, Satan will abandon them completely."
  },
  39: {
    "What harm could have come to them if they had believed in Allah and the Last Day": "This is a rhetorical question challenging those who refuse to believe. What would they have lost by believing? Faith only brings benefit—peace in this life and Paradise in the next. Their refusal harms no one but themselves.",
    "and donated from what Allah has provided for them?": "Similarly, what would they have lost by giving charity? The wealth was from Allah anyway. Giving it in His cause would have brought them rewards far greater than what they gave. Their stinginess only deprives themselves.",
    "And Allah has ˹perfect˺ knowledge of them": "Allah knows their true reasons for disbelief and stinginess—whether it's arrogance, greed, or stubbornness. Nothing is hidden from Him."
  },
  40: {
    "Indeed, Allah never wrongs ˹anyone˺—even by an atom's weight": "Allah is absolutely just. He will not reduce anyone's good deeds by even the smallest amount, nor will He increase anyone's sins beyond what they committed. A dharrah (atom/speck) is used to indicate the smallest possible amount. This verse gives comfort to believers and warning to wrongdoers.",
    "And if it is a good deed, He will multiply it many times over": "Not only does Allah not reduce good deeds, He multiplies them—from ten times to seven hundred times to even more, depending on the sincerity and circumstances. This is pure divine generosity.",
    "and will give a great reward out of His grace": "Beyond the multiplication, Allah gives additional rewards from His own bounty—rewards that are not even earned but given as gifts. This is the generosity of the Most Merciful."
  },
  41: {
    "So how will it be when We bring a witness from every faith-community": "On the Day of Judgment, each nation will have a witness—their prophet—who will testify about whether they received the message and how they responded. No one will be able to claim they were not warned.",
    "and bring you ˹O Prophet˺ as a witness against yours?": "Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) will testify concerning his ummah. When this verse was recited to him, he wept, understanding the weight of this responsibility and the state of those who would reject the message. Abdullah ibn Mas'ud reported that the Prophet asked him to recite Quran, and when he reached this verse, the Prophet said 'Enough' while tears flowed from his eyes."
  },
  42: {
    "On that Day, those who denied ˹Allah˺ and disobeyed the Messenger will wish they were reduced to dust": "The disbelievers will be so terrified and ashamed that they will wish they could simply disappear—that the earth would swallow them up or they could become dust like the ground they stand on. This is the ultimate regret.",
    "And they will never be able to hide anything from Allah": "In this world, people hide their sins, deny their wrongdoing, and lie their way out of consequences. On the Day of Judgment, nothing can be hidden. Allah knows everything, and even their own bodies will testify against them."
  },
  43: {
    "O believers! Do not approach prayer while intoxicated until you are aware of what you say": "This verse was revealed before the complete prohibition of alcohol. It prohibited praying while drunk because prayer requires presence of mind, focus, and understanding of what one is saying. This was a gradual step toward the eventual total ban on intoxicants. The principle remains: approach prayer with a clear, focused mind.",
    "nor in a state of ˹full˺ impurity—unless you merely pass through ˹the mosque˺—until you have bathed": "Janabah (major ritual impurity) occurs after sexual intercourse or emission. In this state, one must perform ghusl (full body bath) before praying. However, one may pass through a mosque without stopping if necessary.",
    "But if you are ill, on a journey, or have relieved yourselves, or been intimate with your wives and cannot find water": "Allah provides concessions for difficult circumstances. If water is unavailable or using it would cause harm (such as for the sick), an alternative is provided.",
    "then purify yourselves with clean earth, wiping your faces and hands": "This is tayammum—a symbolic purification using clean earth or dust when water is unavailable. It involves striking the earth with one's hands and wiping the face and hands. This shows Islam's practicality and consideration for various circumstances.",
    "And Allah is Ever-Pardoning, All-Forgiving": "Allah does not burden people beyond their capacity. He pardons shortcomings and forgives those who try their best within their circumstances."
  },
  44: {
    "Have you ˹O Prophet˺ not seen those who were given a portion of the Scriptures": "This refers to some among the People of the Book (Jews and Christians) who had received divine revelation but did not follow it properly. They had knowledge of scripture but chose to misuse it.",
    "yet trade it for misguidance": "Instead of using their knowledge to find the truth, they traded it for falsehood. They chose misguidance despite knowing better—perhaps for worldly gain, pride, or stubbornness.",
    "and wish to see you deviate from the ˹Right˺ Path?": "Not content with their own misguidance, they actively work to lead Muslims astray. They want the believers to abandon the straight path and join them in error."
  },
  45: {
    "Allah knows best who your enemies are!": "You may not always recognize who truly wishes you harm, but Allah knows every heart. Some enemies pretend to be friends; some apparent friends may have hidden enmity. Trust Allah's knowledge.",
    "And Allah is sufficient as a Guardian, and He is sufficient as a Helper": "With Allah as your protector and helper, you need not fear any enemy. He is enough for those who trust in Him."
  },
  46: {
    "Some Jews take words out of context and say, \"We listen and we disobey,\" \"Hear! May you never hear,\" and \"Râ'ina!\" [Herd us!]—playing with words and discrediting the faith": "This verse describes how some people would twist words to insult the Prophet while appearing polite. 'Ra'ina' sounded like an Arabic word meaning 'give us attention' but in Hebrew could mean an insult. They would pretend to be respectful while actually mocking. They played word games to insult Islam and the Prophet.",
    "Had they said ˹courteously˺, \"We hear and obey,\" \"Listen to us,\" and \"Unẓurna,\" [Tend to us!] it would have been better for them and more proper": "If they had used straightforward, respectful language instead of wordplay, it would have been better for their own souls. Sincerity and respect, even in word choice, matter.",
    "Allah has condemned them for their disbelief, so they do not believe except for a few": "Their mockery and disrespect earned Allah's curse. However, 'except for a few' shows that not all were this way—some were sincere and did believe."
  },
  47: {
    "O you who were given the Book! Believe in what We have revealed—confirming your own Scriptures": "This is a direct call to Jews and Christians to accept the Quran, which confirms the truth in their own scriptures. The Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) was prophesied in their books; the Quran validates the original message of their prophets.",
    "before We wipe out ˹your˺ faces, turning them backwards": "This is a warning of possible punishment—either physical (disfigurement) or metaphorical (being turned away from guidance and truth).",
    "or We condemn the defiant as We did to the Sabbath-breakers": "Reference to those Jews who violated the Sabbath and were transformed into apes as punishment (mentioned in Surah Al-Baqarah 2:65). This reminds them that Allah has punished rebellious communities before.",
    "And Allah's command is always executed!": "When Allah decrees something, nothing can prevent it. His warnings should be taken seriously."
  },
  48: {
    "Indeed, Allah does not forgive associating others with Him ˹in worship˺": "Shirk—worshipping anything or anyone besides Allah—is the only sin that Allah will not forgive if a person dies upon it without repentance. This includes worshipping idols, believing in multiple gods, or directing any act of worship to other than Allah. However, if a person repents from shirk before death, Allah can forgive even this.",
    "but forgives anything else of whoever He wills": "All other sins, no matter how great, are subject to Allah's forgiveness. Murder, adultery, theft—any sin can be forgiven if Allah wills, whether through repentance or simply by His mercy. This gives hope to all sinners except those who die as polytheists.",
    "And whoever associates others with Allah has indeed committed a grave sin": "Shirk is described as a 'grave sin' (ithm 'atheem) because it violates the most fundamental right—Allah's right to be worshipped alone. It is an offense against the Creator Himself and the very purpose of human existence."
  },
  49: {
    "Have you ˹O Prophet˺ not seen those who ˹falsely˺ elevate themselves?": "Some people claim spiritual superiority, saying they are pure, chosen, or guaranteed paradise. This refers to those who boast about their spiritual status without basis.",
    "It is Allah who elevates whoever He wills": "True purification and elevation come from Allah alone. He knows who is truly righteous and who is merely boastful. No one can declare themselves pure; only Allah can purify.",
    "And none will be wronged ˹even by the width of˺ the thread of a date stone": "The 'fateel' is the thin thread-like fiber in the groove of a date stone—something almost invisible. Even this tiny amount will not be taken from anyone's rewards. Allah's justice is perfect."
  },
  50: {
    "See how they fabricate lies against Allah": "Claiming special status with Allah without His authorization is lying about Him. Saying 'We are Allah's chosen people' or 'We will definitely go to paradise' without divine proof is fabrication.",
    "this alone is a blatant sin": "Even without other sins, just lying about Allah is enough to condemn a person. It's a clear, obvious sin that cannot be excused."
  },
  51: {
    "Have you ˹O Prophet˺ not seen those who were given a portion of the Scriptures yet believe in idols and false gods": "Some who received divine scripture abandoned its teachings to believe in 'jibt' (sorcery, idols) and 'taghut' (false deities, tyrants). Despite having knowledge, they chose falsehood.",
    "and reassure the disbelievers that they are better guided than the believers?": "Worse still, they told the pagan Quraysh that their idol worship was better than Islam! This was said by some Jewish leaders who preferred the polytheists over the Muslims—a shocking betrayal of monotheistic principles for political reasons."
  },
  52: {
    "It is they who have been condemned by Allah": "Allah's curse has fallen upon those who preferred polytheism over monotheism and declared idol-worshippers more guided than Muslims.",
    "And whoever is condemned by Allah will have no helper": "When Allah curses someone, no one can protect them. All other helpers are powerless against Allah's decree."
  },
  53: {
    "Do they have control over shares of the kingdom?": "This is a rhetorical question exposing their arrogance. Do they think they control Allah's kingdom and can decide who receives His blessings?",
    "If so, they would not have given anyone so much as the speck on a date stone": "If they had any power over Allah's bounty, their stinginess would prevent them from giving anyone even the tiniest amount. The 'naqeer' is the speck in the groove of a date stone—something worthless. This exposes their mean character."
  },
  54: {
    "Or do they envy the people for Allah's bounties?": "Their real problem is envy—they cannot accept that Allah has blessed Muhammad (peace be upon him) and the Muslims with prophethood and guidance. They wish these blessings were theirs alone.",
    "Indeed, We have given the descendants of Abraham the Book and wisdom, along with great authority": "Allah reminds them that prophethood was never exclusive to one branch of Abraham's family. Allah gave scripture, wisdom, and authority to various descendants of Abraham—including Ishmael's line through Muhammad (peace be upon him). This is Allah's prerogative."
  },
  55: {
    "Yet some believed in him while others turned away from him": "Even among the People of the Book, there was diversity—some accepted the truth while others rejected it. This shows that the door to faith was open, but many chose to close it.",
    "Hell is sufficient as a torment!": "For those who turn away out of arrogance and envy, Hell awaits. Its punishment is more than enough consequence for their rejection."
  },
  56: {
    "Surely those who reject Our signs, We will cast them into the Fire": "Those who deny Allah's revelations—whether the Quran, the signs in creation, or the miracles of the prophets—will face the Fire of Hell.",
    "Whenever their skin is burnt completely, We will replace it so they will ˹constantly˺ taste the punishment": "This vivid description shows the eternality and severity of the punishment. When skin burns, it loses sensation; so Allah will replace it with new skin so the punishment is continuously felt. This is justice for those who persistently rejected truth.",
    "Indeed, Allah is Almighty, All-Wise": "Allah has the power to execute this punishment and the wisdom to assign it justly. No one escapes His might, and His decisions are always wise."
  },
  57: {
    "As for those who believe and do good, We will admit them into Gardens under which rivers flow": "The believers who back up their faith with righteous actions will enter Paradise—gardens of unimaginable beauty with rivers flowing beneath them. This is the reward for faith and good deeds together.",
    "to stay there for ever and ever": "The reward is eternal—not temporary like worldly pleasures. There is no end to the bliss of Paradise.",
    "There they will have pure spouses": "The spouses in Paradise are described as 'mutahharah'—purified from all physical and spiritual impurities. There will be no arguments, jealousy, menstruation, bodily impurities, or bad character—only perfect companionship.",
    "and We will place them under a vast shade": "Paradise offers perfect comfort—cool, pleasant shade that never ends. In contrast to the scorching sun of the Day of Judgment, the believers will enjoy perpetual comfort."
  },
  58: {
    "Indeed, Allah commands you to return trusts to their rightful owners": "'Amanat' (trusts) includes everything entrusted to you—property, secrets, responsibilities, positions of authority. Everything must be returned or fulfilled faithfully. This verse was revealed when the Prophet (peace be upon him) took the keys of the Ka'bah from its custodian Uthman ibn Talhah after the conquest of Makkah, then returned them, establishing that trusteeships should be honored.",
    "and when you judge between people, judge with fairness": "Those in positions of judgment—whether rulers, judges, parents, or arbitrators—must be absolutely fair. No favoritism based on wealth, status, family, or personal feelings. Justice is a divine command.",
    "What a noble commandment from Allah to you!": "Allah praises His own commandment, emphasizing its excellence and importance. Fulfilling trusts and judging fairly are among the highest moral duties.",
    "Surely Allah is All-Hearing, All-Seeing": "Allah hears every dispute and sees every judgment. Nothing is hidden from Him, so judge as if He is watching—because He is."
  },
  59: {
    "O believers! Obey Allah and obey the Messenger": "Obedience to Allah and His Messenger is absolute and unconditional. The repetition of 'obey' emphasizes that the Messenger's authority is directly from Allah. Following the Sunnah is not optional.",
    "and those in authority among you": "This includes rulers, scholars, commanders, and anyone in legitimate authority. Obedience to them is required in matters that don't contradict Islamic law. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said: 'There is no obedience to any creature if it involves disobedience to the Creator.'",
    "Should you disagree on anything, then refer it to Allah and His Messenger": "When disputes arise, the final authority is the Quran and Sunnah—not personal opinion, cultural tradition, or majority vote. This establishes Islamic governance and jurisprudence.",
    "if you ˹truly˺ believe in Allah and the Last Day": "Referring disputes to Allah and His Messenger is a test of faith. Those who truly believe will accept divine guidance over their own preferences.",
    "This is the best and fairest resolution": "Following this method leads to the best outcomes in this world and the next. Human solutions may seem appealing, but divine guidance is always superior."
  },
  60: {
    "Have you ˹O Prophet˺ not seen those who claim they believe in what has been revealed to you and what was revealed before you?": "These are hypocrites who verbally claim faith in all divine revelations but their actions contradict their words.",
    "They seek the judgment of false judges, which they were commanded to reject": "When disputes arose, they would go to pagan judges or unjust courts instead of the Prophet (peace be upon him), hoping for rulings that favored their desires. 'Taghut' refers to any false authority that leads away from Allah's law.",
    "And Satan ˹only˺ desires to lead them farther away": "Their choice to seek judgment from other than Allah plays directly into Satan's plan to lead people astray. Every step away from divine guidance is a step deeper into misguidance."
  },
  61: {
    "When it is said to them, \"Come to Allah's revelations and to the Messenger,\" you see the hypocrites turn away from you stubbornly": "When invited to accept divine judgment, the hypocrites refuse. Their physical turning away reflects the turning of their hearts from truth. They find excuses to avoid submitting to Allah's law because they know it may not favor their desires."
  },
  62: {
    "How ˹horrible˺ will it be if a disaster strikes them because of what their hands have done": "Their wrongdoing eventually catches up with them. When calamity strikes as a consequence of their actions, their hypocrisy becomes more apparent.",
    "then they come to you swearing by Allah, \"We intended nothing but goodwill and reconciliation.\"": "After being caught or facing consequences, they come making excuses, swearing false oaths that they meant well. They claim they were just trying to find a middle ground or make peace. This is the behavior of hypocrites—denial and false justification when exposed."
  },
  63: {
    "˹Only˺ Allah knows what is in their hearts": "Even if they deceive people with their words, Allah knows the reality of their hearts. No one can hide their true intentions from Him.",
    "So turn away from them, caution them, and give them advice that will shake their very souls": "The Prophet is advised to (1) not let their behavior distract him, (2) warn them of consequences, and (3) speak to them in a way that penetrates their hearts—words that are eloquent, serious, and reach deep into their conscience. Sometimes harsh truth is necessary for someone drowning in self-deception."
  },
  64: {
    "We only sent messengers to be obeyed by Allah's Will": "The purpose of sending messengers is that they be followed, not just heard. A messenger rejected is a mission failed. Obedience to prophets is obedience to Allah.",
    "If only those ˹hypocrites˺ came to you ˹O Prophet˺—after wronging themselves—seeking Allah's forgiveness and the Messenger prayed for their forgiveness": "The door of repentance remains open. If the hypocrites sincerely repented for their wrongs and came to the Prophet asking him to pray for their forgiveness...",
    "they would have certainly found Allah ever Accepting of Repentance, Most Merciful": "Allah would have forgiven them. This shows the vastness of divine mercy and the value of the Prophet's intercession. But they must come sincerely, not with excuses."
  },
  65: {
    "But no! By your Lord, they will never be ˹true˺ believers until they accept you ˹O Prophet˺ as the judge in their disputes": "Allah swears by Himself—a most serious oath—that true faith requires accepting the Prophet's judgment. Not just externally, but as the final authority in all matters of dispute.",
    "and find no resistance within themselves against your decision": "True faith means no inner resentment when the Prophet rules. The heart should be at peace with his judgment even if it goes against one's desires. This is the test of sincere faith.",
    "and submit wholeheartedly": "Complete submission (tasleem) is required—not grudging compliance, not partial acceptance, but wholehearted surrender to the Prophet's rulings. This is what it means to truly believe."
  },
  66: {
    "If We had commanded them to sacrifice themselves or abandon their homes, none would have obeyed except for a few": "Allah reveals how weak their faith really is. If they struggle to accept simple rulings, imagine if they were commanded with severe tests like those given to previous nations. Only the truly sincere few would obey.",
    "Had they done what they were advised to do, it would have certainly been far better for them and more reassuring": "Following divine guidance—even when difficult—always leads to better outcomes. Obedience strengthens faith and brings inner peace, while disobedience brings anxiety and weakness."
  },
  67: {
    "and We would have granted them a great reward by Our grace": "Had they obeyed, Allah would have rewarded them generously—not just according to their deeds but with additional bounty from His grace. Obedience opens doors of divine reward."
  },
  68: {
    "and guided them to the Straight Path": "Obedience leads to more guidance. Those who follow what they know are given more knowledge and clearer direction. The straight path becomes increasingly clear to those who walk upon it."
  },
  69: {
    "And whoever obeys Allah and the Messenger will be in the company of those blessed by Allah": "This is one of the most beautiful promises in the Quran. Obedience to Allah and His Messenger earns companionship with the greatest people in Paradise.",
    "the prophets": "The highest rank—those chosen by Allah to deliver His message to humanity.",
    "the people of truth": "As-Siddiqeen are those who always speak the truth, accept the truth immediately, and live by the truth. Abu Bakr (may Allah be pleased with him) earned this title for his immediate acceptance of the Prophet's message.",
    "the martyrs": "Ash-Shuhada are those who died in Allah's cause. They are alive with their Lord, provided for, and honored.",
    "and the righteous": "As-Saliheen are the general righteous believers who did good deeds throughout their lives.",
    "what honourable company!": "What better companions could one ask for? This verse was revealed when a companion was sad thinking about being separated from the Prophet in Paradise, and Allah reassured the believers that obedience ensures eternal companionship with the best of creation."
  },
  70: {
    "This is Allah's favour": "Reaching such company is not due to one's merit alone but is Allah's grace and favor. No one earns Paradise through deeds alone; it is ultimately Allah's mercy.",
    "and Allah fully knows ˹who deserves it˺": "Allah knows who is truly sincere in their obedience and who deserves this honor. Nothing is hidden from Him."
  },
  71: {
    "O believers! Take your precautions": "When facing enemies, believers must be prepared. This includes military readiness, intelligence gathering, strategic planning, and maintaining vigilance. Faith does not mean recklessness.",
    "and go forth either in groups or together": "Depending on the situation, believers may advance in smaller units or as a unified force. This shows tactical flexibility while maintaining collective effort."
  },
  72: {
    "There will be some among you who will lag behind": "This exposes the hypocrites who find excuses to avoid participating in legitimate struggle. They hang back while others sacrifice.",
    "so that if you face a disaster, they will say, \"Allah has blessed us for not being there among them.\"": "If the believers suffer losses, the hypocrites congratulate themselves on their 'wisdom' in staying behind. They see avoiding sacrifice as divine favor, when in reality their cowardice deprives them of honor."
  },
  73: {
    "But if you return with Allah's bounties, they will say—as if there had been no bond between you—\"We wish we had been there with them to share the great gain!\"": "When the believers return victorious with booty and honor, the same hypocrites express regret for not joining! They want the benefits without the sacrifice. They speak 'as if there had been no bond'—meaning they show no loyalty when it costs them something, but suddenly claim closeness when there is profit. This exposes their true motivation: worldly gain, not faith."
  },
  74: {
    "Let those who would sacrifice this life for the Hereafter fight in the cause of Allah": "True believers prioritize eternal reward over temporary worldly comfort. They are willing to sacrifice their lives for Allah's cause. This is not glorifying war but encouraging those who believe to stand up for justice and truth.",
    "And whoever fights in Allah's cause—whether they achieve martyrdom or victory—We will honour them with a great reward": "Both outcomes are victories. If killed, they become martyrs with all its rewards. If victorious, they have honored Allah's cause. Either way, a great reward awaits. There is no losing when fighting for Allah."
  },
  75: {
    "And what is it with you? You do not fight in the cause of Allah": "This is a strong reproach. What excuse could there be for not fighting when the cause is just?",
    "and for oppressed men, women, and children": "Fighting in Islam is not about conquest or domination but about liberating the oppressed. When innocent men, women, and children are being persecuted and cannot defend themselves, those who are able have a responsibility to help them. This is jihad in its truest sense—struggle against injustice.",
    "who cry out, \"Our Lord! Deliver us from this land of oppressors!\"": "The oppressed are calling out to Allah, begging for rescue from those who persecute them. Their cry should move believers to action.",
    "Appoint for us a saviour; appoint for us a helper—all by Your grace": "The oppressed seek a 'wali' (protector/guardian) and 'naseer' (helper) from Allah. This du'a shows their trust in Allah to send someone to deliver them. Throughout Islamic history, Allah has answered such prayers by raising up those who fought for the rights of the oppressed."
  },
  76: {
    "Believers fight for the cause of Allah": "Those who truly believe fight for a noble purpose—to establish Allah's justice, protect the oppressed, defend their faith, and earn Allah's pleasure. Their motivation is not worldly gain, nationalism, or personal glory, but solely the cause of Allah. This purifies their intention and elevates their struggle.",
    "whereas disbelievers fight for the cause of the Devil": "Those who oppose truth fight for 'taghut'—false deities, tyrannical systems, and ultimately Satan's agenda. Whether they realize it or not, those who fight against Allah's cause are serving Satan's interests. Their struggle, no matter how powerful it appears, is fundamentally misguided.",
    "So fight against Satan's ˹evil˺ forces": "The command is clear: confront those who serve Satan's agenda. The 'awliya' (allies/forces) of Satan are those who do his bidding, spreading corruption and oppression. Believers should not be intimidated by them.",
    "Indeed, Satan's schemes are ever weak": "This is a tremendous source of comfort and courage for believers. No matter how elaborate Satan's plots appear, they are fundamentally weak because they are built on falsehood. Allah's plan always prevails. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said that Satan flees when he hears the adhan. A being that runs from a simple call to prayer cannot withstand those who truly rely on Allah. When believers trust in Allah, Satan's tricks crumble."
  },
  77: {
    "Have you ˹O Prophet˺ not seen those who had been told, \"Do not fight! Rather, establish prayer and pay alms-tax.\"?": "In the early Makkan period, Muslims were persecuted but commanded to be patient and not retaliate. Some companions, eager to defend themselves, would ask for permission to fight. They were told to restrain themselves and focus on spiritual development through prayer and charity.",
    "Then once the order came to fight, a group of them feared those ˹hostile˺ people as Allah should be feared—or even more": "When permission to fight finally came in Madinah, a strange reversal happened. Some of the same people who had been eager to fight now became afraid. They feared the enemy armies more than they feared Allah—or even more intensely! This exposes a weakness in their faith. When fighting was forbidden, they wanted it; when it was permitted, they feared it. This inconsistency reveals that their earlier eagerness may not have been purely for Allah's sake.",
    "They said, \"Our Lord! Why have You ordered us to fight? If only You had delayed ˹the order for˺ us for a little while!\"": "They questioned Allah's wisdom and wished for delay. 'Just a little more time to enjoy life,' they thought. This reveals attachment to worldly comfort over obedience to Allah. They were not ready to sacrifice because their hearts were still tied to this temporary world.",
    "Say, ˹O Prophet,˺ \"The enjoyment of this world is so little": "The Prophet is commanded to remind them of reality. All worldly pleasures—wealth, comfort, safety, long life—are temporary and insignificant compared to eternity. Even if one lived a hundred years in luxury, it is nothing compared to endless time in the Hereafter.",
    "whereas the Hereafter is far better for those mindful ˹of Allah˺": "For those with taqwa (God-consciousness), the Hereafter holds rewards beyond imagination—eternal paradise, Allah's pleasure, and the company of the righteous. Why cling to something temporary when something infinitely better awaits?",
    "And none of you will be wronged ˹even by the width of˺ the thread of a date stone": "The 'fateel' is the thin thread in a date stone—almost worthless. Allah assures that not even this tiny amount will be unjustly taken from anyone's rewards. Every sacrifice, every moment of fear overcome for Allah's sake, will be fully compensated. Nothing is lost with Allah."
  },
  78: {
    "Wherever you may be, death will overcome you—even if you were in fortified towers": "This verse destroys the illusion that avoiding battle preserves life. Death is decreed by Allah and will find everyone at their appointed time, regardless of where they hide. Whether in the strongest fortress, the safest bunker, or the most remote location—when your time comes, nothing can delay it. So why let fear of death prevent you from doing what is right? The coward dies at the same time as the brave; the difference is how they lived.",
    "When something good befalls them, they say, \"This is from Allah,\"": "When the hypocrites experience good fortune—victory, wealth, health—they acknowledge it as Allah's blessing. This much is correct.",
    "but when something evil befalls them, they say, \"This is from you.\"": "However, when hardship strikes—defeat, loss, suffering—they blame the Prophet (peace be upon him) and the believers. They said the presence of Muslims brought bad luck. This is the attitude of hypocrites throughout history: take credit for good, blame others for bad.",
    "Say, ˹O Prophet,˺ \"Both have been destined by Allah.\"": "The Prophet is told to clarify: everything—good and bad—occurs by Allah's decree. Nothing happens without His permission. This is the Islamic understanding of qadr (divine destiny). Allah is in control of all affairs.",
    "So what is the matter with these people? They can hardly comprehend anything!": "Allah expresses amazement at their lack of understanding. Despite having the truth explained to them, they refuse to grasp basic concepts of faith. Their problem is not intellectual but spiritual—their hearts are sealed due to their hypocrisy."
  },
  79: {
    "Whatever good befalls you is from Allah": "Every blessing, success, and good fortune comes from Allah's grace and mercy. Even our ability to do good deeds is a gift from Him. We should never attribute our successes purely to our own abilities but recognize Allah's favor.",
    "and whatever evil befalls you is from yourself": "This complements the previous verse. While everything happens by Allah's decree, the calamities we face are often consequences of our own sins and mistakes. Allah allows hardship to come as a result of our choices. This teaches personal responsibility—don't blame others or even divine destiny for problems that stem from your own actions. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said: 'A person is deprived of provision because of sins they commit.' This verse encourages self-reflection when facing difficulties.",
    "We have sent you ˹O Prophet˺ as a messenger to ˹all˺ people": "Muhammad (peace be upon him) was not sent only to the Arabs or to a specific nation, but to all of humanity until the Day of Judgment. His message is universal—every human being is addressed by his prophethood.",
    "And Allah is sufficient as a Witness": "Allah witnesses the Prophet's delivery of the message and witnesses how people respond. No one can deny receiving the message when Allah Himself is the Witness."
  },
  80: {
    "Whoever obeys the Messenger has truly obeyed Allah": "This is a foundational principle of Islam. Obedience to the Prophet (peace be upon him) is not separate from obedience to Allah—it IS obedience to Allah. The Prophet's commands, teachings, and Sunnah carry divine authority. Those who claim to follow Allah but reject the Prophet's guidance are deceiving themselves. You cannot have one without the other.",
    "But whoever turns away, then ˹know that˺ We have not sent you ˹O Prophet˺ as a keeper over them": "The Prophet's duty is to deliver the message, not to force people to accept it. Those who turn away are responsible for their own choices. This relieves the Prophet of feeling responsible for everyone's guidance—he did his job; their rejection is on them. This also establishes that faith cannot be compelled."
  },
  81: {
    "And they say, \"We obey,\"": "In the Prophet's presence, the hypocrites would declare their obedience and loyalty. Their words sounded perfect—respectful, agreeable, compliant.",
    "but when they leave you, a group of them would spend the night contradicting what they said": "The moment they left the Prophet's company, their true nature emerged. 'Bayyata' means they would spend the night plotting and scheming against what they had publicly agreed to. Their nights were spent in conspiracy, their days in pretense. This is the essence of hypocrisy: saying one thing publicly and doing the opposite privately.",
    "Allah records all their schemes": "Nothing is hidden from Allah. Every whispered plot, every secret meeting, every contradictory plan is recorded. They may think their nighttime conspiracies are secret, but Allah documents everything. This is both a warning to hypocrites and comfort to believers—Allah knows who is sincere and who is not.",
    "So turn away from them": "Don't let their schemes consume your attention or cause you distress. Recognize them for what they are and don't be disturbed by their plotting.",
    "and put your trust in Allah": "Tawakkul (reliance on Allah) is the believer's response to hypocrites and enemies. Rather than anxiety and counter-scheming, place your affairs in Allah's hands. He is the best planner.",
    "And Allah is sufficient as a Trustee of Affairs": "Allah is 'wakeel'—the One who takes care of all affairs for those who trust Him. When you have Allah managing your affairs, you need no other protector or strategist. He is enough."
  },
  82: {
    "Do they not then reflect on the Quran?": "This is a powerful invitation to engage deeply with the Quran. 'Tadabbur' means to ponder, contemplate, and reflect carefully—not just to read or recite superficially. Allah challenges people to think critically about the Quran. True reflection leads to recognizing its divine origin. The Quran welcomes scrutiny because it has nothing to hide. Those who reflect sincerely will find guidance; those who approach it with closed hearts will remain blind.",
    "Had it been from anyone other than Allah, they would have certainly found in it many inconsistencies": "This is a remarkable challenge. The Quran was revealed over 23 years, in different places, addressing various situations, covering law, history, science, spirituality, and prophecy—yet it contains no contradictions. Human works, no matter how carefully edited, contain inconsistencies over time. Authors change views, make mistakes, or contradict themselves. The Quran's perfect internal harmony—despite being revealed piecemeal over two decades—is evidence of its divine source. Every claim is consistent, every teaching harmonious, every prophecy accurate. This consistency is impossible for human authorship."
  },
  83: {
    "And when they hear news of security or fear, they publicize it": "Some people, when they hear any news—whether reassuring or alarming—immediately spread it without verification. They share rumors about victories, defeats, threats, or safety without confirming the truth. This behavior causes confusion, panic, or false hope. In times of war especially, unverified information can be devastating. This verse addresses a timeless problem that is even more relevant in our age of instant social media sharing.",
    "Had they referred it to the Messenger or their authorities, those with sound judgment among them would have validated it": "The proper approach is to take unverified news to those qualified to assess it—leaders, scholars, experts who can investigate and determine what is true. 'Istinbat' means to extract the truth, to investigate properly. Not everyone is qualified to evaluate sensitive information. This establishes a principle: refer matters to those with knowledge and authority rather than spreading unconfirmed reports.",
    "Had it not been for Allah's grace and mercy, you would have followed Satan—except for a few": "Without Allah's guidance and protection, people would easily fall into Satan's traps—spreading lies, causing panic, and creating division. Only by Allah's mercy are believers saved from these pitfalls. The 'few' who would have been saved refers to those with exceptional wisdom and self-control, showing how rare such qualities are without divine assistance."
  },
  84: {
    "So fight in the cause of Allah ˹O Prophet˺": "This is a direct command to the Prophet (peace be upon him) to engage in legitimate struggle for Allah's cause. Fighting here is defensive—protecting the Muslim community and establishing justice.",
    "You are accountable for none but yourself": "This profound statement establishes individual responsibility. Even if others refuse to fight, the Prophet must do his duty. He is not responsible for forcing others to join; he is responsible for his own obedience to Allah. This principle applies to all believers: you cannot control others' choices, but you are responsible for your own. Do your duty regardless of how many join you.",
    "And motivate the believers ˹to fight˺": "While not responsible for others' choices, the Prophet should still encourage and inspire them. 'Tahreed' means to urge, motivate, and inspire. Leadership involves both personal example and encouraging others to excellence.",
    "so perhaps Allah will curb the disbelievers' might": "The outcome is in Allah's hands. Fighting with faith may cause Allah to restrain the enemy's power. Victory comes from Allah, not from numbers or weapons alone.",
    "And Allah is far superior in might and in punishment": "No matter how powerful the enemy appears, Allah is infinitely more powerful. His might ('ba's') and His punishment ('tankeel') surpass anything humans can muster. This provides courage to believers facing seemingly overwhelming odds."
  },
  85: {
    "Whoever intercedes for a good cause will have a share in the reward": "If you help someone achieve something good—whether by recommendation, support, advocacy, or assistance—you share in the reward of that good. This encourages Muslims to be helpful, to use their influence for good causes, to recommend people for jobs they deserve, to support charitable efforts, and to facilitate good in any way possible. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said: 'Intercede and you will be rewarded.' Even if your intercession is not accepted, you are rewarded for trying.",
    "and whoever intercedes for an evil cause will have a share in the burden": "The reverse is equally true. If you help someone commit wrong—by recommending an unqualified person, supporting injustice, covering for wrongdoers, or facilitating sin—you share in the sin. This should make people careful about what they support, recommend, or facilitate. Don't use your influence for evil.",
    "And Allah is Watchful over all things": "'Muqeet' means the One who witnesses, maintains, and has power over all things. Allah sees every intercession—good or bad—and will recompense accordingly. Nothing escapes His knowledge."
  },
  86: {
    "And when you are greeted, respond with a better greeting or at least similarly": "Islam emphasizes good manners in all interactions, including something as simple as greetings. When someone says 'Assalamu Alaikum' (Peace be upon you), you should respond with 'Wa Alaikum Assalam wa Rahmatullahi wa Barakatuh' (And upon you be peace, and Allah's mercy and blessings)—adding to what they said. At minimum, return the same greeting. Never respond with less than what was given. This builds a society of mutual respect and warmth. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said: 'You will not enter Paradise until you believe, and you will not believe until you love one another. Shall I tell you something that if you do it, you will love one another? Spread the greeting of peace among yourselves.'",
    "Surely Allah is a ˹vigilant˺ Reckoner of all things": "Even something as small as returning a greeting is recorded by Allah. He takes account of everything—the small courtesies as well as the major deeds. This should motivate believers to perfect even the smallest aspects of their character."
  },
  87: {
    "Allah, there is no god ˹worthy of worship˺ except Him": "This is the declaration of Tawhid—absolute monotheism. Allah alone deserves worship; there is no deity besides Him. This fundamental truth is the foundation of Islam and the message of every prophet.",
    "He will certainly gather ˹all of˺ you together on the Day of Judgment": "Resurrection is certain. Every human being who ever lived will be gathered before Allah for accounting. The word 'la-yajma'annakum' contains emphasis (the lam of oath and the nun of emphasis), making this an emphatic promise.",
    "about which there is no doubt": "The Day of Judgment is not a possibility or a theory—it is an absolute certainty. Allah removes any room for doubt. Those who deny it do so against clear evidence and divine declaration.",
    "And whose word is more truthful than Allah's?": "This rhetorical question establishes Allah as the ultimate source of truth. No one's word is more reliable, more honest, or more certain than Allah's. When Allah makes a promise, it will absolutely be fulfilled. If Allah says the Day of Judgment will come, it will come without any doubt."
  },
  97: {
    "When the angels seize the souls of those who have wronged themselves—scolding them, \"What do you think you were doing?\"": "At death, the angels will question those who lived among disbelievers without trying to practice their faith or escape. 'Wronged themselves' means they harmed their own souls by remaining in a situation where they couldn't practice Islam. The question 'What were you doing?' demands an explanation for their choices.",
    "they will reply, \"We were oppressed in the land.\"": "Their excuse is that they were weak and oppressed—unable to practice Islam openly or resist the pressure around them. They claim they had no choice.",
    "The angels will respond, \"Was Allah's earth not spacious enough for you to emigrate?\"": "The angels reject this excuse. Allah's earth is vast. If one place is hostile to your faith, move to another. This establishes the principle that Muslims should not remain in situations where they cannot practice their religion if they have the ability to leave. Emigration (hijrah) becomes obligatory when one cannot practice Islam and has the means to relocate.",
    "It is they who will have Hell as their home—what an evil destination!": "Those who could have emigrated but chose comfort over faith will face Hell. This is a severe warning against choosing worldly ease over religious commitment when alternatives exist."
  },
  98: {
    "Except helpless men, women, and children who cannot afford a way out": "This exception shows Allah's perfect justice. Those who are genuinely unable to emigrate—the truly weak, the imprisoned, the elderly, women without male guardians to travel with, children, the poor who lack resources—are not blamed. They lack both the means ('heelah' - resources, strategy) and the knowledge of how to emigrate ('sabeel' - a way, path). Their situation is genuinely beyond their control."
  },
  99: {
    "it is right to hope that Allah will pardon them": "For the genuinely helpless, there is hope of Allah's pardon. The word ''asa' (it is hoped/expected) from Allah indicates strong likelihood—when Allah expresses hope for something, it essentially means He will do it.",
    "For Allah is Ever-Pardoning, All-Forgiving": "Allah's names Al-'Afuw (The Pardoner) and Al-Ghafoor (The Forgiving) are emphasized. He pardons completely (erasing sins as if they never happened) and forgives (covering faults with mercy). Those who were genuinely unable to emigrate can trust in Allah's comprehensive mercy."
  },
  100: {
    "Whoever emigrates in the cause of Allah will find many safe havens and bountiful resources throughout the earth": "'Muraghaman' means places of refuge where one can escape the enemy and live with dignity. 'Sa'ah' means spaciousness, abundance, and provision. Allah promises that those who leave their homes for His sake will find alternatives. The earth is not limited to one location. Those who sacrifice one home for Allah's sake will find others. This was proven by the early Muslims who emigrated to Abyssinia and Madinah—they found safety, community, and provision.",
    "Those who leave their homes and die while emigrating to Allah and His Messenger—their reward has already been secured with Allah": "This addresses those who begin the journey of emigration but die before completing it. Even if they never reach their destination, their reward is guaranteed with Allah. The intention combined with the action of leaving is enough. The Prophet (peace be upon him) mentioned a man from Banu Layth who left to emigrate but died on the way—his reward was complete. This shows that Allah rewards sincere intention backed by genuine effort, even if the goal is not achieved.",
    "And Allah is All-Forgiving, Most Merciful": "Any shortcomings in the emigration—perhaps imperfect intention, regrets, or difficulties—are covered by Allah's forgiveness and mercy."
  },
  101: {
    "When you travel through the land, it is permissible for you to shorten the prayer": "This establishes the concession of 'qasr'—shortening the four-unit prayers (Dhuhr, Asr, Isha) to two units while traveling. Islam recognizes the difficulty of travel and provides ease. The Prophet (peace be upon him) practiced this throughout his life while traveling. Umar (may Allah be pleased with him) asked the Prophet about this concession, and he said: 'It is a charity from Allah to you, so accept His charity.'",
    "˹especially˺ if you fear an attack by the disbelievers": "The verse mentions fear of enemy attack as a context, but the Prophet's practice showed that shortening applies to all travel, not just dangerous journeys. The mention of fear here highlights the additional reason during times of conflict.",
    "Indeed, the disbelievers are your sworn enemies": "This reminder contextualizes why caution is needed. The enmity of disbelievers toward believers is clear ('mubeen')—open and obvious. This justifies both the military alertness and the prayer concessions during hostile conditions."
  },
  102: {
    "When you ˹O Prophet˺ are ˹campaigning˺ with them and you lead them in prayer, let one group of them pray with you—while armed": "This describes 'Salat al-Khawf'—the prayer of fear, performed during active military engagement. The army divides into two groups. One group prays with the imam while carrying weapons.",
    "When they prostrate themselves, let the other group stand guard behind them": "After the first group completes their portion, they move to guard positions while still armed, protecting the congregation.",
    "Then the group that has not yet prayed will then join you in prayer—and let them be vigilant and armed": "The second group then comes to pray, also carrying their weapons and remaining alert. This ensures continuous protection while still fulfilling the obligation of congregational prayer. Prayer is never abandoned, even in battle.",
    "The disbelievers would wish to see you neglect your weapons and belongings, so they could launch a sweeping assault on you": "The enemy hopes Muslims will be distracted during prayer, creating an opportunity for attack. This verse warns against that vulnerability while showing that Islam doesn't require believers to be defenseless during worship.",
    "But there is no blame if you lay aside your weapons when overcome by heavy rain or illness—but take precaution": "Concessions exist even within concessions. If carrying weapons is impractical due to weather or sickness, there is no sin in setting them aside—but mental alertness should remain.",
    "Indeed, Allah has prepared a humiliating punishment for the disbelievers": "This reassurance reminds believers that regardless of the enemy's plots, Allah has prepared their ultimate defeat and humiliation."
  },
  103: {
    "When the prayers are over, remember Allah—whether you are standing, sitting, or lying down": "Even after the formal prayer ends, remembrance of Allah should continue in all positions—while marching, resting, or wounded. Dhikr (remembrance) is not limited to any posture and should fill the believer's moments, especially during dangerous times.",
    "But when you are secure, establish regular prayers": "When the danger passes and safety returns, the full prayers must be performed properly without shortcuts. The concessions during danger do not become permanent habits; they are temporary allowances.",
    "Indeed, performing prayers is a duty on the believers at the appointed times": "Prayer is 'kitaban mawqutan'—a prescribed obligation at fixed times. It cannot be abandoned, even in war. The times are set by Allah, and believers must fulfill this duty whether in comfort or difficulty. This verse establishes that prayer times are fixed and obligatory—one of the most important principles of Islamic worship."
  },
  104: {
    "Do not falter in pursuit of the enemy": "'Wahn' means weakness, slackness, or losing resolve. Believers should not become weak or give up when pursuing a just cause against enemies. Persistence is required even when tired or suffering setbacks.",
    "if you are suffering, they too are suffering": "This puts hardship in perspective. Whatever pain, exhaustion, or losses the believers experience, the enemy experiences the same. Battle is hard for both sides. Neither has a monopoly on suffering. So why should believers be the ones to give up?",
    "But you can hope to receive from Allah what they can never hope for": "Here is the crucial difference: believers have hope in Allah's reward—victory in this life, forgiveness of sins, martyrdom leading to Paradise, and eternal reward. The disbelievers have none of this. They suffer the same pain but with no divine hope, no eternal reward, no spiritual purpose. This difference should give believers the edge in perseverance.",
    "And Allah is All-Knowing, All-Wise": "Allah knows the full picture—the struggles, the sacrifices, the hidden intentions, and the ultimate outcomes. His wisdom guides events toward the best conclusion. Trust His plan and persist."
  },
  105: {
    "Indeed, We have sent down the Book to you ˹O Prophet˺ in truth": "The Quran was revealed with absolute truth—no falsehood in its content, its guidance, or its judgments. It is the criterion by which all matters are decided.",
    "to judge between people by means of what Allah has shown you": "The Prophet's role includes being a judge among people, and his judgments must be based on divine guidance, not personal opinion or external pressure. 'What Allah has shown you' refers to the Quran, the Sunnah, and divine inspiration that guides the Prophet's decisions.",
    "So do not be an advocate for the deceitful": "This verse was revealed regarding a case where a man from the Ansar stole a suit of armor and hid it with a Jewish neighbor, then blamed the Jew. Some people pressured the Prophet to defend the thief because he was Muslim. Allah warns against advocating for those who are guilty simply because of tribal, religious, or personal connections. Justice must be blind to such considerations. A 'khaseem' is someone who argues on behalf of another—the Prophet is told never to argue in defense of traitors or the deceitful."
  },
  106: {
    "And seek Allah's forgiveness": "Even the Prophet, who is protected from sin, is commanded to seek forgiveness. This teaches humility and constant turning to Allah. For ordinary believers, seeking forgiveness is even more essential. Some scholars say this may refer to seeking forgiveness for having initially considered the case favorably before the truth was revealed.",
    "indeed, Allah is All-Forgiving, Most Merciful": "Allah's forgiveness is always available for those who sincerely seek it. His mercy encompasses all who turn to Him in repentance."
  },
  107: {
    "Do not advocate for those who wrong themselves": "Those who deceive and sin are ultimately harming themselves most. 'Yakhtanoon anfusahum' means they betray their own souls. By defending such people, one becomes complicit in their self-destruction.",
    "Surely Allah does not like those who are deceitful, sinful": "'Khawwan' (extremely treacherous) and 'atheem' (deeply sinful) are intensive forms, describing habitual, serious wrongdoing. Allah does not love such people, which is a severe condemnation. Being beloved to Allah is the greatest achievement; being disliked by Him is the greatest loss."
  },
  108: {
    "They try to hide ˹their deception˺ from people, but they can never hide it from Allah": "The deceitful are concerned about their reputation among humans but forget that Allah sees everything. They may successfully conceal their plots from people, but nothing is hidden from Allah. This is a fundamental problem—fearing people's judgment more than Allah's.",
    "in Whose presence they plot by night what is displeasing to Him": "'Yubayyitoon' means they spend the night planning and scheming evil. In the darkness, they think no one sees them, but Allah is with them, witnessing every whisper, every plot, every intention. Their nighttime conspiracies are fully known to Him.",
    "And Allah is Fully Aware of what they do": "'Muheetan' means Allah's knowledge surrounds and encompasses everything they do. Nothing escapes Him—not the act, not the intention, not the consequences."
  },
  109: {
    "Here you are! You ˹believers˺ are advocating for them in this life": "This is a direct address to those who defended the guilty party. You may argue on their behalf now, in this temporary world, using your influence or rhetoric.",
    "but who will ˹dare to˺ advocate for them before Allah on the Day of Judgment?": "On the Day of Judgment, when they stand before Allah with their crimes exposed, who will dare to defend them then? No lawyer, no influential friend, no tribal leader will step forward to argue their case before the Lord of the Worlds.",
    "Or who will come to their defence?": "Who will be their 'wakeel'—their representative, their defender? No one will take on that role against Allah. This rhetorical question exposes the futility of defending the guilty now when they will stand alone then."
  },
  110: {
    "Whoever commits evil or wrongs themselves": "'Su'' (evil) may refer to sins that harm others, while 'wronging oneself' may refer to sins that primarily harm the sinner—though all sins ultimately wrong oneself. Both categories are covered.",
    "then seeks Allah's forgiveness will certainly find Allah All-Forgiving, Most Merciful": "This is a beautiful promise. No matter what sin you have committed, if you sincerely turn to Allah in repentance, you will find Him ready to forgive. The verse guarantees it—'yajid' (will find). This keeps the door of hope open for all sinners. The thief mentioned in the story could have repented rather than adding to his sin by blaming an innocent person."
  },
  111: {
    "And whoever commits a sin—it is only to their own loss": "Sin may harm others temporarily, but ultimately, the sinner bears the true burden. The consequences of sin—guilt, spiritual darkness, punishment in the Hereafter—fall upon the one who commits it. You cannot truly harm Allah by disobeying Him; you only harm yourself.",
    "Allah is All-Knowing, All-Wise": "Allah knows every sin committed and, in His wisdom, assigns consequences accordingly. Nothing escapes His knowledge, and His judgment is always wise and just."
  },
  112: {
    "And whoever commits an evil or sinful deed then blames it on an innocent person": "This directly addresses what the thief did—committing theft then falsely accusing an innocent man. This compounding of sin upon sin is extremely serious.",
    "they will definitely bear the guilt of slander and blatant sin": "Now they carry two burdens: (1) 'buhtan'—slander, false accusation, which is itself a major sin, and (2) 'ithm mubeen'—a clear, obvious sin that cannot be excused. The original sin was bad enough; adding false accusation makes it far worse. This teaches that covering one sin with another only multiplies guilt."
  },
  113: {
    "Had it not been for Allah's grace and mercy, a group of them would have sought to deceive you ˹O Prophet˺": "Allah protected the Prophet from being misled by the false case presented to him. Without divine intervention, the plotters might have succeeded in making the Prophet rule unjustly, which would have harmed his reputation and mission.",
    "Yet they would deceive none but themselves": "Their plot backfired. By attempting to deceive the Prophet, they only increased their own sin and exposed their own treachery. The deceiver ultimately deceives only themselves.",
    "nor can they harm you in the least": "Allah guarantees the Prophet's protection. No plot against him can succeed in causing real harm to him or his mission. This is reassurance for the Prophet and a warning to his enemies.",
    "Allah has revealed to you the Book and wisdom and taught you what you never knew": "Allah blessed the Prophet with (1) the Quran (the Book), (2) wisdom (hikmah—the Sunnah, understanding, and insight), and (3) knowledge he never had before. The Prophet was unlettered before prophethood; all his knowledge came from divine teaching.",
    "Great ˹indeed˺ is Allah's favour upon you!": "The sum of all these blessings—protection, revelation, wisdom, knowledge—constitutes an immense favor from Allah. The Prophet should recognize this and remain grateful, and the enemies should recognize they are fighting against Allah's chosen messenger."
  },
  114: {
    "There is no good in most of their secret talks": "'Najwa' refers to private conversations, whispered discussions, confidential meetings. Most such talk is useless or harmful—gossip, plotting, backbiting, or empty chatter. Allah declares there is no 'khayr' (good) in most of it.",
    "except those encouraging charity": "Private conversations that promote giving, whether encouraging oneself or others to give charity, are good and beneficial.",
    "kindness": "'Ma'roof' encompasses all good deeds—helping others, doing what is right, promoting virtue. Conversations that encourage good behavior are valuable.",
    "or reconciliation between people": "One of the most meritorious acts is bringing peace between people who are in conflict. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said: 'Shall I not inform you of something better than fasting, prayer, and charity? It is reconciling people.' Making peace between spouses, family members, friends, or community members is highly rewarded.",
    "And whoever does this seeking Allah's pleasure, We will grant them a great reward": "The key condition is intention—'ibtighaa mardaatillah' (seeking Allah's pleasure). If these good deeds are done for Allah's sake, not for reputation or personal gain, the reward is 'great' ('atheem')—a term indicating tremendous recompense."
  },
  115: {
    "And whoever defies the Messenger after guidance has become clear to them": "'Yushaqiq' means to oppose, resist, or create division from the Messenger. This is not about genuine ignorance but willful defiance after the truth is clearly understood. Such people know the right path but deliberately turn away.",
    "and follows a path other than that of the believers": "This phrase is significant for Islamic jurisprudence. It establishes that following the consensus (ijma') of the believers is obligatory. Separating from the community of believers and taking one's own way is dangerous. The 'way of the believers' is the way of the Prophet's companions and those who follow them sincerely.",
    "We will let them pursue what they have chosen": "Allah gives them what they wanted—their own misguided path. This is a form of punishment: being left to follow one's misguidance without divine guidance or protection.",
    "then burn them in Hell—what an evil end!": "The final destination of such people is Hellfire. After letting them wander in their chosen misguidance in this life, Allah will cast them into Hell forever. 'What an evil end' emphasizes the horror of this fate."
  },
  116: {
    "Surely Allah does not forgive associating ˹others˺ with Him ˹in worship˺": "Shirk—directing any worship to other than Allah—is the only sin that Allah will not forgive if one dies upon it without repentance. This is repeated in the Quran to emphasize its severity. However, if a person repents from shirk before death, Allah can forgive even this.",
    "but forgives anything else of whoever He wills": "Every other sin—no matter how severe—is subject to Allah's forgiveness. He may forgive through repentance, through good deeds, through hardships that expiate sins, or simply through His mercy. This gives hope to all sinners except those who die as polytheists.",
    "Indeed, whoever associates ˹others˺ with Allah has clearly gone far astray": "'Dalala ba'eeda' (far astray) describes someone who has wandered so far from the path that returning becomes extremely difficult. Shirk takes one far from truth, far from Allah, far from salvation."
  },
  117: {
    "Instead of Allah, they only invoke female gods": "The pagans of Arabia worshipped female deities like Al-Lat, Al-Uzza, and Manat, considering them daughters of Allah (which Allah refutes). They also gave feminine names to angels and worshipped them. Despite their pride in masculinity, they worshipped what they considered lesser beings.",
    "and they ˹actually˺ invoke none but a rebellious Satan": "Behind all idol worship is Satan. Whatever names or forms the idols take, worshipping them is really worshipping Satan, who set up this system of polytheism. 'Mareed' describes Satan as rebellious, obstinate, and utterly defiant of Allah."
  },
  118: {
    "cursed by Allah": "Satan is permanently expelled from Allah's mercy. This curse is his eternal fate.",
    "who said, \"I will surely take hold of a certain number of Your servants\"": "Satan declared his intention to claim a portion of humanity. 'Naseeban mafroodan' suggests a fixed, determined portion—he is committed to misleading as many as possible. This is his mission and his satisfaction—corrupting Allah's creation."
  },
  119: {
    "I will certainly mislead them": "Satan's first tactic is leading people away from truth—making falsehood appear attractive and truth appear burdensome.",
    "and delude them with empty hopes": "'Umanniyannuhum'—he fills them with false hopes: 'You can repent later,' 'Hell is not real,' 'Allah will surely forgive,' 'Enjoy now and worry later.' These empty promises lead people to procrastinate repentance.",
    "Also, I will order them and they will slit the ears of cattle": "This refers to pagan practices of marking animals for idols by cutting their ears. Satan commands religious innovations and superstitious practices.",
    "and alter Allah's creation": "This encompasses changing what Allah has created—whether through prohibited body modifications, genetic tampering, or corrupting the natural disposition (fitrah) that Allah placed in humans. Satan wants humans to deform themselves and their nature.",
    "And whoever takes Satan as a guardian instead of Allah has certainly suffered a tremendous loss": "Choosing Satan as one's 'wali' (protector, ally) instead of Allah results in 'khusran mubeen'—a clear, obvious, devastating loss. Satan promises but never delivers; Allah promises and always fulfills."
  },
  120: {
    "Satan only makes them ˹false˺ promises and deludes them with ˹empty˺ hopes": "This summarizes Satan's methodology. He promises pleasure, success, and delayed consequences, but none of his promises are real.",
    "Truly Satan promises them nothing but delusion": "'Ghuroor' means deception, delusion, false appearances. Everything Satan offers is a mirage—beautiful from afar but nothing when you arrive. His promises evaporate, leaving only regret."
  },
  121: {
    "It is they who will have Hell as their home": "Those who follow Satan will end up in Hellfire—their permanent dwelling ('ma'wa').",
    "and they will find no escape from it": "'Mahees' means a place of escape or refuge. They will search for a way out but find none. Hell is inescapable for those condemned to it."
  },
  122: {
    "And those who believe and do good, We will soon admit them into Gardens under which rivers flow": "In contrast to Satan's followers, the believers who combine faith with righteous action will enter Paradise—gardens of eternal beauty with rivers flowing beneath them.",
    "to stay there for ever and ever": "'Khalideen feeha abada' emphasizes permanence—not just a long time, but eternal, forever. The joy never ends.",
    "Allah's promise is ˹always˺ true": "Unlike Satan's false promises, Allah's promise is 'haqqa'—true, real, and certain. When Allah promises Paradise, it is guaranteed.",
    "And whose word is more truthful than Allah's?": "This rhetorical question establishes Allah as the ultimate source of truth. No one's word is more reliable. If you must trust someone's promise, trust Allah's."
  },
  123: {
    "˹Divine grace is˺ neither by your wishes nor those of the People of the Book!": "Salvation is not achieved through wishful thinking. Muslims cannot say 'We are guaranteed Paradise because we are Muslim,' just as Jews and Christians cannot claim automatic salvation. Empty claims without righteous action mean nothing.",
    "Whoever commits evil will be rewarded accordingly": "This is the universal law: you reap what you sow. Sin has consequences regardless of your religious identity. No group is exempt from accountability.",
    "and they will find no protector or helper besides Allah": "When facing the consequences of sin, no one can protect or help except Allah. No tribal connection, no religious label, no wealth or influence will help."
  },
  124: {
    "But those who do good—whether male or female—and have faith will enter Paradise": "The formula for Paradise is clear: faith plus good deeds. Both are required, and both are available to men and women equally. Gender does not determine one's potential for reward.",
    "and will never be wronged ˹even as much as˺ the speck on a date stone": "The 'naqeer' is the tiny speck in the groove of a date stone—virtually worthless. Not even this much will be unjustly taken from their rewards. Allah's justice is perfect."
  },
  125: {
    "And who is better in faith than those who ˹fully˺ submit themselves to Allah": "'Aslama wajhahu' means to surrender one's face—one's entire self, direction, and being—to Allah. Complete submission is the essence of Islam.",
    "do good": "'Muhsin' describes one who does things excellently, with perfection and sincerity. It's not just doing good but doing it beautifully for Allah's sake.",
    "and follow the Way of Abraham, the upright?": "'Millat Ibrahim' is the pure monotheistic way of Abraham, free from polytheism and deviation. 'Haneef' means one who turns away from all falsehood toward pure truth. This is the path all prophets followed.",
    "Allah chose Abraham as a close friend": "'Khaleel' is a level of friendship beyond ordinary friendship—an intimate, exclusive relationship. Abraham was given this unique honor. The Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) said: 'If I were to take a khaleel from this ummah, I would have taken Abu Bakr, but your companion [referring to himself] is the khaleel of Allah.' This shows Abraham's exceptional status."
  },
  126: {
    "To Allah ˹alone˺ belongs whatever is in the heavens and whatever is on the earth": "Allah is the owner of everything. Nothing exists outside His dominion. This ownership means He has full authority over all creation.",
    "And Allah is Fully Aware of everything": "'Muheetan' means Allah's knowledge encompasses and surrounds everything. Nothing is outside His awareness—every thought, every action, every hidden matter."
  },
  127: {
    "They ask you ˹O Prophet˺ regarding women. Say, \"It is Allah Who instructs you regarding them": "People asked the Prophet about various rulings concerning women. Allah answers directly, emphasizing that these rulings come from Him, not from cultural preferences.",
    "Instruction has ˹already˺ been revealed in the Book concerning the orphan women you deprive of their due rights but still wish to marry": "This refers back to verse 4:3. Some guardians wanted to marry orphan women under their care to control their wealth, but without giving them fair dowries. They wanted the benefit of the marriage without fulfilling the woman's rights.",
    "also helpless children": "Allah also instructs regarding weak, vulnerable children who cannot defend themselves. Their rights must be protected.",
    "as well as standing up for orphans' rights": "'Qist' means justice and fairness. Standing up for orphans' rights is a repeated theme because orphans are easily exploited.",
    "And whatever good you do is certainly well known to Allah": "Every act of kindness toward women, orphans, and the vulnerable is recorded by Allah. He knows and will reward accordingly."
  },
  128: {
    "If a woman fears indifference or neglect from her husband, there is no blame on either of them if they seek ˹fair˺ settlement": "When a wife notices her husband becoming distant or neglectful—perhaps he wants to divorce her or marry another—they can negotiate a settlement. She might agree to forgo some of her rights (like some nights or financial support) to preserve the marriage. This happened with Sawdah (may Allah be pleased with her), who gave her night to Aisha to remain married to the Prophet.",
    "which is best": "'Sulh is khair'—reconciliation and settlement is better than divorce. Islam encourages saving marriages when possible.",
    "Humans are ever inclined to selfishness": "'Shuhh' means extreme stinginess or selfishness. Human nature inclines toward protecting self-interest, which can make compromise difficult. But marriage requires sacrifice and compromise from both sides.",
    "But if you are gracious and mindful ˹of Allah˺, surely Allah is All-Aware of what you do": "If spouses show grace, forgiveness, and taqwa, Allah sees and rewards it. Good conduct in marriage, even when difficult, does not go unnoticed."
  },
  129: {
    "You will never be able to maintain ˹emotional˺ justice between your wives—no matter how keen you are": "Complete emotional equality between wives is impossible. The heart's inclinations cannot be perfectly controlled. A man might love one wife more than another, and this is beyond his control.",
    "So do not totally incline towards one leaving the other in suspense": "While emotional equality is impossible, material fairness is required. Don't neglect one wife so completely that she is 'mu'allaqah'—suspended, neither properly married nor divorced. Give each wife her rights of time, support, and dignity even if emotional attachment varies.",
    "And if you do what is right and are mindful ˹of Allah˺, surely Allah is All-Forgiving, Most Merciful": "If you try your best to be fair despite natural emotional limitations, Allah will forgive shortcomings and show mercy."
  },
  130: {
    "But if they choose to separate, Allah will enrich both of them from His bounties": "If reconciliation fails and divorce becomes necessary, both parties should trust that Allah will provide for them. Divorce is not the end—Allah's provision is vast. Each can find happiness and sustenance separately.",
    "And Allah is Ever-Bountiful, All-Wise": "Allah's bounty ('sa'ah') is limitless, and His wisdom determines what is best for each person. Sometimes separation, though painful, is the wisest outcome."
  },
  131: {
    "To Allah ˹alone˺ belongs whatever is in the heavens and whatever is on the earth": "Allah's ownership is total and absolute. This is repeated to emphasize His sovereignty.",
    "Indeed, We have commanded those given the Scripture before you, as well as you, to be mindful of Allah": "Taqwa (mindfulness of Allah) was commanded to all previous nations and to Muslims. It is the universal teaching of all divine revelations.",
    "But if you disobey, then ˹know that˺ to Allah belongs whatever is in the heavens and the earth": "Your disobedience does not harm Allah in the least. He owns everything and needs nothing from you. Your obedience benefits you; your disobedience harms you.",
    "And Allah is Self-Sufficient, Praiseworthy": "'Ghaniyy' means Allah needs nothing from anyone. 'Hameed' means He is worthy of all praise regardless of whether creation praises Him. His perfection is independent of human acknowledgment."
  },
  132: {
    "To Allah ˹alone˺ belongs whatever is in the heavens and whatever is on the earth": "The repetition drives home this fundamental truth.",
    "And Allah is sufficient as a Trustee of Affairs": "Allah is the perfect 'wakeel'—manager and disposer of all affairs. Those who trust Him need no other support."
  },
  133: {
    "If it is His Will, He can remove you altogether, O humanity, and replace you with others": "This is a reminder of human dispensability. Allah does not need us. If all humans were to disobey, He could simply remove them and create a new, obedient creation. This should inspire humility and gratitude for the opportunity to worship and be rewarded.",
    "And Allah is Most Capable to do so": "This is not an empty threat—Allah has full power to execute this if He willed. His ability is unlimited."
  },
  134: {
    "Whoever desires the reward of this world, then ˹let them know that˺ with Allah are the rewards of this world and the Hereafter": "Some people only work for worldly gain—wealth, fame, power. But they should know that Allah controls both worldly and eternal rewards. Why settle for just worldly benefit when you could have both? Why not ask Allah, who owns everything, for both worlds?",
    "And Allah is All-Hearing, All-Seeing": "Allah hears all requests and sees all intentions. He knows who is working for this world alone and who seeks both worlds."
  },
  135: {
    "O believers! Stand firm for justice as witnesses for Allah": "'Qawwameen bil-qist' means to be upholders, establishers, and maintainers of justice—not occasionally, but consistently. Being a witness 'for Allah' means your testimony aims to please Allah, not to benefit yourself or others unjustly.",
    "even if it is against yourselves, your parents, or close relatives": "True justice requires testifying truthfully even when it harms your own interests, even when it goes against your beloved parents, even when it exposes your closest relatives. This is extremely difficult but essential for a just society.",
    "Be they rich or poor, Allah is best to ensure their interests": "Don't let someone's wealth intimidate you or someone's poverty invoke false sympathy. Don't favor the rich out of hope for their favor, or the poor out of misplaced compassion. Allah knows what is best for both and will take care of them. Your job is to speak the truth.",
    "So do not let your desires cause you to deviate ˹from justice˺": "'Hawa' (desires) should never influence testimony or judgment. Personal likes, dislikes, benefits, or fears must not distort justice.",
    "If you distort the testimony or refuse to give it, then ˹know that˺ Allah is certainly All-Aware of what you do": "'Talwoo' means to distort or twist testimony. 'Tu'ridoo' means to refuse to testify when you have knowledge. Both are sinful. Allah is 'khabeer'—fully aware of every detail. You cannot hide the truth from Him."
  },
  136: {
    "O believers! Have faith in Allah": "Even those who already believe are called to believe—meaning to increase, renew, and perfect their faith. Faith is not static; it should grow continuously.",
    "His Messenger": "Faith in Muhammad (peace be upon him) as Allah's final messenger is essential. This includes following his guidance and accepting his authority.",
    "the Book He has revealed to His Messenger": "The Quran—the final, preserved revelation that supersedes previous scriptures.",
    "and the Scriptures He revealed before": "The original Torah, Gospel, Psalms, and other divine scriptures—believing that they were originally from Allah, though later altered by human hands.",
    "Indeed, whoever denies Allah, His angels, His Books, His messengers, and the Last Day has clearly gone far astray": "These are the pillars of faith. Denying any one of them takes a person 'far astray' (dalalan ba'eeda)—not just slightly off course but completely lost. These beliefs are fundamental and interconnected; rejecting one undermines all."
  },
  137: {
    "Indeed, those who believed then disbelieved, then believed and again disbelieved": "This describes people who treat faith like a revolving door—entering and exiting as convenient. They embrace Islam when it benefits them, leave when it becomes difficult, return when circumstances change, then abandon it again. This pattern shows they never had sincere faith.",
    "˹only˺ increasing in disbelief": "Each cycle of apostasy deepens their disbelief. Rather than learning from their experiences, they become more entrenched in rejection. Their hearts become harder with each return to disbelief.",
    "Allah will neither forgive them nor guide them to the ˹Right˺ Way": "For such persistent waverers who die in disbelief, there is no forgiveness and no guidance. They have played games with their faith so many times that Allah seals their hearts. This is not because Allah cannot forgive, but because they have demonstrated complete insincerity and will not genuinely repent."
  },
  138: {
    "Give good news of a painful punishment to hypocrites": "This is bitter sarcasm. 'Good news' (bashara) is typically used for glad tidings, but here it sarcastically announces punishment. The hypocrites who thought they were clever, playing both sides, will receive painful torment. Their 'reward' for their deception is suffering."
  },
  139: {
    "who choose disbelievers as allies instead of the believers": "The hypocrites align themselves with disbelievers against the Muslim community. They share secrets with enemies, support them financially or politically, and prefer their company over that of sincere believers.",
    "Do they seek honour and power through that company?": "The rhetorical question exposes their motivation—they think allying with powerful disbelievers will bring them honor, status, or security. They calculate that the disbelievers might win, so they hedge their bets.",
    "Surely all honour and power belongs to Allah": "Their calculation is fundamentally flawed. True 'izzah' (honor, power, dignity) belongs entirely to Allah. He grants it to whom He wills. Seeking honor from those who reject Allah is seeking it from an empty source. Only through Allah can genuine honor be achieved."
  },
  140: {
    "He has already revealed to you in the Book that when you hear Allah's revelations being denied or ridiculed": "This refers to a previous revelation in Surah Al-An'am (6:68). When people mock, deny, or make fun of Allah's verses, the Quran, Islam, or the Prophet, believers must respond appropriately.",
    "then do not sit in that company unless they engage in a different topic": "The command is clear: leave such gatherings. Don't be a passive audience to blasphemy or mockery. You may return only if they change the subject to something permissible. This applies to physical gatherings, online forums, social media discussions, and any setting where Islam is being ridiculed.",
    "or else you will be like them": "Silent approval makes you a participant. By staying and listening without objection or leaving, you become complicit in their sin. Your presence legitimizes their mockery.",
    "Surely Allah will gather the hypocrites and disbelievers all together in Hell": "Those who mock and those who silently approve will share the same destination. The hypocrites who sat with mockers, enjoying the 'humor' while claiming to be Muslim, will join the disbelievers in Hell."
  },
  141: {
    "˹The hypocrites are˺ those who wait to see what happens to you": "'Yatarabbasoon' means they watch from the sidelines, waiting to see which side wins before committing. They are strategic opportunists who never take a principled stand.",
    "So if Allah grants you victory, they say ˹to you˺, \"Were we not on your side?\"": "When Muslims win, hypocrites rush to claim association. 'We were with you all along! Count us among the victorious!' They want a share of the spoils without having shared the risk.",
    "But if the disbelievers have a share ˹of victory˺, they say ˹to them˺, \"Did we not have the advantage over you, yet we protected you from the believers?\"": "When disbelievers gain ground, hypocrites rush to their side, claiming credit for helping them. 'We had inside information on the Muslims but didn't use it fully against you. We protected you.' They try to collect rewards from both sides.",
    "Allah will judge between ˹all of˺ you on the Day of Judgment": "This double-dealing will be exposed and judged. On that Day, their true allegiance will be revealed.",
    "And Allah will never grant the disbelievers a way over the believers": "Ultimately, true believers will prevail. Allah promises that disbelievers will never have ultimate authority or permanent victory over sincere believers—whether in this world or the next."
  },
  142: {
    "Surely the hypocrites seek to deceive Allah, but He outwits them": "The hypocrites think their pretense fools Allah, but He knows their reality completely. 'He outwits them' means He lets them continue in their delusion, gives them rope to hang themselves, and prepares their punishment while they think they're succeeding.",
    "When they stand up for prayer, they do it half-heartedly": "'Kusala' means lazily, reluctantly, with heaviness. They drag themselves to prayer with no enthusiasm. Their bodies pray while their hearts are elsewhere. This describes the outer form without inner spirit.",
    "only to be seen by people": "'Riya'' (showing off) is their motivation. They pray not for Allah but for social acceptance, to maintain their cover as Muslims. If no one was watching, they wouldn't pray at all.",
    "hardly remembering Allah at all": "Even during prayer, their minds wander everywhere except to Allah. They recite without understanding, bow without humility, and prostrate without submission. Their remembrance of Allah is minimal and insincere."
  },
  143: {
    "Torn between belief and disbelief—belonging neither to these ˹believers˺ nor those ˹disbelievers˺": "'Mudhabdhabeen' describes someone swaying, wavering, unstable—like something blown by wind from side to side. They cannot commit to either side. Not truly Muslim, not openly kafir. This is the worst position—at least the open disbeliever has clarity.",
    "And whoever Allah leaves to stray, you will never find for them a way": "When Allah allows someone to go astray due to their persistent insincerity, no one can guide them. The Prophet himself cannot guide those whom Allah has left in misguidance. Guidance is Allah's gift, and hypocrisy forfeits it."
  },
  144: {
    "O believers! Do not take disbelievers as allies instead of the believers": "This is a direct command to the Muslim community. 'Awliya'' in this context means close allies, confidants, protectors—those with whom you share secrets and upon whom you rely against your own community. Normal interactions, business dealings, and neighborly relations are not prohibited, but deep alliance that compromises Muslim interests is forbidden.",
    "Would you like to give Allah solid proof against yourselves?": "By allying with those who oppose Islam against fellow Muslims, you provide clear evidence for your own punishment. On the Day of Judgment, such behavior will stand as proof of hypocrisy or weak faith."
  },
  145: {
    "Surely the hypocrites will be in the lowest depths of the Fire": "'Darak al-asfal' is the lowest, deepest level of Hell—worse than the level of open disbelievers. Hypocrites are punished more severely because their crime is worse: they pretended to believe while secretly rejecting, causing harm from within the Muslim community.",
    "and you will never find for them any helper": "In the deepest Hell, no one will come to their aid. No intercessor, no rescuer, no relief. Their isolation is complete."
  },
  146: {
    "except those who repent": "The door of repentance remains open even for hypocrites. Sincere tawbah (repentance) can save them from the lowest Hell.",
    "mend their ways": "'Aslahu' means to correct, reform, and fix what was broken. Repentance must be followed by changing behavior and repairing damage done.",
    "hold fast to Allah": "'I'tasamu billah'—to grip tightly to Allah, seeking refuge in Him alone, relying on Him completely. This is the opposite of seeking protection from disbelievers.",
    "and are sincere in their devotion to Allah": "'Akhlasu deenahum lillah'—making their religion purely for Allah, removing all hypocrisy, showing off, and mixed intentions. Sincerity (ikhlas) is the cure for hypocrisy.",
    "they will be with the believers": "Those who fulfill these conditions are no longer hypocrites—they join the ranks of true believers.",
    "And Allah will grant the believers a great reward": "The reward for true faith is immense—not just escape from Hell, but Paradise and Allah's pleasure."
  },
  147: {
    "Why should Allah punish you if you are grateful and faithful?": "This rhetorical question reveals Allah's nature. He doesn't punish for the sake of punishment. If you believe and are grateful, what reason would Allah have to punish you? His punishment is a consequence of disbelief and ingratitude, not arbitrary cruelty.",
    "Allah is ever Appreciative, All-Knowing": "'Shakir' means Allah appreciates and rewards even small acts of gratitude and faith. 'Aleem' means He knows exactly who is sincere. He won't overlook genuine faith or miss hidden hypocrisy."
  },
  148: {
    "Allah does not like negative thoughts to be voiced": "Generally, Islam discourages speaking evil—backbiting, slander, public complaints, cursing, and spreading negativity. Allah does not love such speech.",
    "except by those who have been wronged": "The exception is for victims of injustice. They may speak out about the wrong done to them—to seek help, to warn others, or to seek justice. A person who has been cheated may name the cheater. An abuse victim may speak about the abuser. This is not forbidden negative speech but legitimate recourse.",
    "Allah is All-Hearing, All-Knowing": "Allah hears both the wrongdoer and the victim. He knows who truly was wronged and who is making false claims. This reminder ensures the exception isn't abused."
  },
  149: {
    "Whether you reveal or conceal a good": "Good deeds can be done publicly (to encourage others) or privately (for greater sincerity). Both are rewarded based on intention.",
    "or pardon an evil": "While the victim has the right to speak out, pardoning is even better. Forgiving those who wronged you, letting go of grievances—this is a higher path.",
    "surely Allah is Ever-Pardoning, Most Capable": "'Afuww' (Ever-Pardoning) shows Allah loves to pardon, so He loves when His servants pardon others. 'Qadeer' (Most Capable) indicates that Allah has full power to punish but chooses to pardon—teaching us that true strength is in forgiving when you have the power to retaliate."
  },
  150: {
    "Surely those who deny Allah and His messengers": "This addresses those who claim to believe in God but reject His messengers, or accept some messengers while rejecting others.",
    "and wish to make a distinction between Allah and His messengers": "They try to separate belief in God from belief in His messengers—accepting God but rejecting prophets, or accepting prophets selectively.",
    "saying, \"We believe in some and disbelieve in others,\"": "This was the practice of Jews (accepting Moses but rejecting Jesus and Muhammad) and Christians (accepting Jesus but rejecting Muhammad). Selective belief in prophets is rejection of all, because all prophets came with the same essential message from the same God.",
    "desiring to forge a compromise": "They want a middle path—partial faith that satisfies their preferences while rejecting what they dislike. Islam doesn't allow such pick-and-choose religion."
  },
  151: {
    "they are indeed the true disbelievers": "'Kafireen haqqan'—disbelievers in reality, in truth. Despite their claims of partial belief, they are truly disbelievers because rejecting one messenger means rejecting the One who sent all messengers.",
    "And We have prepared for the disbelievers a humiliating punishment": "Their punishment will include humiliation—fitting for those who arrogantly picked and chose among Allah's messengers."
  },
  152: {
    "As for those who believe in Allah and His messengers—accepting all; rejecting none": "True believers accept all prophets without discrimination. They believe in Adam, Noah, Abraham, Moses, Jesus, Muhammad, and all prophets mentioned or unmentioned in the Quran.",
    "He will surely give them their rewards": "Complete faith earns complete reward. Those who accept the whole message will receive their full recompense.",
    "And Allah is All-Forgiving, Most Merciful": "Allah forgives past ignorance when one comes to true faith and shows mercy to those who submit completely."
  },
  153: {
    "The People of the Book demand that you ˹O Prophet˺ bring down for them a revelation in writing from heaven": "Some Jews asked Prophet Muhammad to bring down a physical book from the sky as proof. This was a demand for miracles on their terms, not sincere inquiry.",
    "They demanded what is even greater than this from Moses, saying, \"Make Allah visible to us!\"": "Their ancestors made an even more outrageous demand of Moses—to see Allah directly. This shows a pattern of making impossible demands to avoid believing.",
    "So a thunderbolt struck them for their wrongdoing": "Their arrogant demand brought divine punishment—they were struck by lightning for their transgression.",
    "Then they took the calf for worship after receiving clear signs": "Despite witnessing miracles, they worshipped a golden calf when Moses was away. This shows how quickly they abandoned faith despite overwhelming evidence.",
    "Still We forgave them for that ˹after their repentance˺ and gave Moses compelling proof": "Allah's mercy is vast. Despite their terrible sin, when they repented, He forgave them and continued to support Moses with clear authority and miracles."
  },
  154: {
    "We raised the Mount over them ˹as a warning˺ for ˹breaking˺ their covenant": "Mount Sinai was raised above them as a powerful sign when they hesitated to accept the covenant. This dramatic intervention compelled them to take their commitment seriously.",
    "and said, \"Enter the gate ˹of Jerusalem˺ with humility.\"": "When entering Jerusalem, they were commanded to enter humbly, bowing in gratitude. Instead, some entered mockingly.",
    "We also warned them, \"Do not break the Sabbath,\"": "Observing the Sabbath was a strict commandment. They were forbidden from working or fishing on Saturday.",
    "and took from them a firm covenant": "The covenant was solemn and serious ('ghaleetha' - firm, heavy, binding). Breaking it would have severe consequences."
  },
  155: {
    "˹They were condemned˺ for breaking their covenant": "Their punishment came because they violated the solemn promises they made to Allah.",
    "rejecting Allah's signs": "They denied the miracles and revelations sent to them despite clear evidence.",
    "killing the prophets unjustly": "They killed prophets sent to guide them—a crime of the highest magnitude.",
    "and for saying, \"Our hearts are unreceptive!\"": "They claimed their hearts were wrapped up, unable to receive new guidance—using this as an excuse for rejection.",
    "it is Allah Who has sealed their hearts for their disbelief": "Their claim was false—their hearts weren't naturally unreceptive; rather, Allah sealed them as punishment for persistent disbelief.",
    "so they do not believe except for a few": "Only a small minority among them accepted truth—like Abdullah ibn Salam and other righteous individuals who embraced Islam."
  },
  156: {
    "and for their denial and outrageous accusation against Mary": "Some Jews accused Mary (Maryam) of fornication—a terrible slander against one of the most righteous women in history. This 'buhtan atheem' (monstrous slander) added to their sins."
  },
  157: {
    "and for boasting, \"We killed the Messiah, Jesus, son of Mary, the messenger of Allah.\"": "Some boasted about killing Jesus, though ironically they called him 'Messenger of Allah' (perhaps sarcastically, or this is the Quran's description). They took pride in what they thought was his execution.",
    "But they neither killed nor crucified him—it was only made to appear so": "This is the Islamic position on the crucifixion. Jesus was not killed or crucified—it was made to appear that way. 'Shubbiha lahum' means it was made to seem so to them. Many scholars say another person was made to look like Jesus and was crucified in his place.",
    "Even those who argue for this ˹crucifixion˺ are in doubt": "Those who claim certainty about the crucifixion are actually uncertain. There has been historical debate even among Christians about details.",
    "They have no knowledge whatsoever—only making assumptions": "Their belief is based on assumption (dhann), not certain knowledge. They followed what they thought happened, not verified truth.",
    "They certainly did not kill him": "This emphatic repetition reinforces the Islamic position—Jesus was definitely not killed by them."
  },
  158: {
    "Rather, Allah raised him up to Himself": "Instead of being killed, Jesus was raised by Allah to the heavens. He is alive with Allah, saved from his enemies. This is the Islamic belief about Jesus's end on earth—not death by crucifixion but elevation to Allah.",
    "And Allah is Almighty, All-Wise": "Allah had the power to save His messenger and the wisdom to do so in a way that tested people's faith and exposed the truth."
  },
  159: {
    "Every one of the People of the Book will definitely believe in him before his death": "This verse has two main interpretations: (1) Before each individual from the People of the Book dies, they will believe in Jesus truthfully—perhaps at the moment of death when reality becomes clear. (2) Before Jesus's death—meaning when Jesus returns before the Day of Judgment, all People of the Book will believe in him as a prophet, not as God or son of God.",
    "And on the Day of Judgment Jesus will be a witness against them": "Jesus will testify against those who rejected him and those who made false claims about him—whether denying his prophethood or exaggerating him to divinity."
  },
  160: {
    "We forbade the Jews certain foods that had been lawful to them for their wrongdoing": "As punishment for their sins, Allah prohibited certain foods that were originally permissible—such as fat of cattle and sheep, and some other animals. These restrictions were punitive, not arbitrary.",
    "and for hindering many from the Way of Allah": "They not only strayed themselves but actively prevented others from following truth. This compounded their sin."
  },
  161: {
    "taking interest despite its prohibition": "Riba (interest/usury) was forbidden in their scripture, yet they practiced it extensively. This economic exploitation was a major sin.",
    "and consuming people's wealth unjustly": "Beyond interest, they used various means to take others' money unfairly—fraud, manipulation, dishonest dealings.",
    "We have prepared for the disbelievers among them a painful punishment": "Not all Jews are condemned—only 'the disbelievers among them.' Those who rejected truth and practiced these sins face painful punishment."
  },
  162: {
    "But those of them well-grounded in knowledge": "'Rasikhoon fil-'ilm'—those with deep, firm knowledge. Not superficial learners but scholars who understood the truth of their scriptures.",
    "the faithful ˹who˺ believe in what has been revealed to you ˹O Prophet˺ and what was revealed before you": "They accept both the Quran and previous revelations, recognizing the continuity of Allah's message.",
    "˹especially˺ those who establish prayer": "Prayer is highlighted as a distinguishing practice of the sincere.",
    "and those who pay alms-tax and believe in Allah and the Last Day": "They fulfill financial obligations (zakat) and hold correct beliefs about Allah and the Hereafter.",
    "to these ˹people˺ We will grant a great reward": "The righteous among the People of the Book who accept Islam will receive tremendous reward—equal to any other believer."
  },
  163: {
    "Indeed, We have sent revelation to you ˹O Prophet˺ as We sent revelation to Noah and the prophets after him": "Muhammad's prophethood follows the same pattern as all previous prophets. He received revelation just as they did—he is not an innovation but a continuation.",
    "We also sent revelation to Abraham, Ishmael, Isaac, Jacob, and his descendants": "The Abrahamic line of prophets all received divine revelation.",
    "˹as well as˺ Jesus, Job, Jonah, Aaron, and Solomon": "Various prophets from different times and contexts are named—showing the breadth of Allah's guidance throughout history.",
    "And to David We gave the Psalms": "David received the Zabur (Psalms)—confirming that multiple scriptures were revealed, not just the Torah."
  },
  164: {
    "There are messengers whose stories We have told you already and others We have not": "The Quran mentions some prophets by name and story, but many others are not mentioned. Tradition suggests there were 124,000 prophets throughout history. We don't know all their names.",
    "And to Moses Allah spoke directly": "Moses had the unique honor of direct speech with Allah—hence his title 'Kaleemullah' (the one Allah spoke to). This was a special distinction."
  },
  165: {
    "˹All were˺ messengers delivering good news and warnings": "Every prophet came with both glad tidings for the obedient and warnings for the disobedient. This dual message is consistent throughout.",
    "so humanity should have no excuse before Allah after ˹the coming of˺ the messengers": "The purpose of sending so many messengers is to remove any excuse on the Day of Judgment. No one can say, 'We didn't know' or 'No one warned us.' Allah sent guidance to every nation.",
    "And Allah is Almighty, All-Wise": "Allah's power ensured the message reached humanity, and His wisdom determined when and how to send each messenger."
  },
  166: {
    "Yet ˹if you are denied, O Prophet,˺ Allah bears witness to what He has sent down to you": "Even if humans reject, Allah Himself testifies to the truth of the Quran. This divine testimony outweighs any human denial.",
    "He has sent it with His knowledge": "The Quran contains Allah's knowledge—perfect, complete, and without error. It wasn't the Prophet's invention but divine revelation.",
    "The angels too bear witness": "The angels, including Jibril who delivered the revelation, also testify to its truth.",
    "And Allah ˹alone˺ is sufficient as a Witness": "Allah's testimony alone is enough. Even without any human or angelic witness, Allah's witness is complete and sufficient proof."
  },
  167: {
    "Those who disbelieve and hinder ˹others˺ from the Way of Allah have certainly strayed far away": "Those who not only disbelieve themselves but actively prevent others from believing have gone extremely far astray. They combine personal rejection with the crime of misleading others."
  },
  168: {
    "Those who disbelieve and wrong themselves—surely Allah will neither forgive them nor guide them to any path": "Those who combine disbelief with persistent wrongdoing lose access to forgiveness and guidance. Their fate is sealed if they die in that state."
  },
  169: {
    "except that of Hell, to stay there for ever and ever": "The only path left for such people leads to Hell—eternal residence with no escape.",
    "And that is easy for Allah": "Executing this punishment is effortless for Allah. His power is unlimited. Those who thought they could escape or that Allah couldn't punish them are gravely mistaken."
  },
  170: {
    "O humanity! The Messenger has certainly come to you with the truth from your Lord": "This is a universal address to all human beings—not just Arabs, not just the people of that time, but all of humanity across all generations. The Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) came with absolute truth from the Lord of all worlds. This truth is not his own invention but divine revelation from Allah, your Creator and Sustainer.",
    "so believe for your own good": "The command to believe is followed by a reminder that faith benefits YOU, not Allah. Believing brings you guidance, peace, purpose in this life, and salvation in the Hereafter. Faith is in your own interest.",
    "But if you disbelieve, then ˹know that˺ to Allah belongs whatever is in the heavens and the earth": "Your disbelief doesn't harm Allah in the slightest. He owns everything—every star, every planet, every creature. He is completely independent and self-sufficient. Your rejection only harms yourself.",
    "And Allah is All-Knowing, All-Wise": "Allah knows who believes and who rejects, and in His wisdom, He will deal with each accordingly. Nothing escapes His knowledge, and His decisions are always wise."
  },
  171: {
    "O People of the Book! Do not go to extremes regarding your faith": "'Ghuluww' means to exceed proper bounds, to exaggerate, to go to extremes. This addresses Christians primarily, who elevated Jesus beyond his true status. Extremism in religion—whether exaggerating the status of prophets or saints, or adding practices not sanctioned by God—leads to deviation. The Jews went to one extreme by rejecting Jesus entirely; the Christians went to the other extreme by deifying him. Islam calls for the balanced middle path.",
    "say nothing about Allah except the truth": "All statements about Allah must be true and verified. Claiming Allah has a son, or is part of a trinity, or has partners—these are false statements about Allah that must be avoided.",
    "The Messiah, Jesus, son of Mary, was no more than a messenger of Allah": "This clarifies Jesus's true status. He was a messenger—honored, noble, miraculous, but still a human messenger. 'Son of Mary' emphasizes his human birth and maternal lineage, implicitly denying any divine paternity.",
    "and the fulfilment of His Word through Mary": "Jesus was created through Allah's word 'Be!' (Kun). Allah's command was delivered to Mary, and Jesus came into existence. The 'word' refers to the creative command, not that Jesus himself is the eternal Word of God in a divine sense.",
    "and a spirit ˹created by a command˺ from Him": "'Rooh minhu'—a spirit from Him. This means Jesus was given life by Allah's command, just as Adam was. 'From Him' indicates origin of creation, not that Jesus is part of Allah's essence. Allah breathed life into Jesus as He did with Adam. This does not make Jesus divine any more than it makes Adam divine.",
    "So believe in Allah and His messengers": "True faith requires believing in Allah as One and in all His messengers, including Jesus—but as a messenger, not as God.",
    "and do not say, \"Trinity.\"": "The doctrine of Trinity—Father, Son, and Holy Spirit as three persons in one God—is explicitly rejected. This concept developed after Jesus and contradicts pure monotheism.",
    "Stop!—for your own good": "'Intahu'—cease, stop, desist! This is a strong command. Abandoning the Trinity doctrine is for their own benefit, not Allah's.",
    "Allah is only One God": "Tawheed—the absolute oneness of Allah—is the core message of all prophets. There is only one God, not three, not two, but ONE.",
    "Glory be to Him! He is far above having a son!": "'Subhanahu'—He is exalted, glorified, and far beyond such limitations. Having a child implies need, dependency, physicality—attributes that don't apply to Allah. He is the Creator, not a creature who reproduces.",
    "To Him belongs whatever is in the heavens and whatever is on the earth": "Everything is His creation and possession—including Jesus. The Owner doesn't become one of His possessions.",
    "And Allah is sufficient as a Trustee of Affairs": "Allah manages all affairs perfectly. He needs no son, no partner, no helper."
  },
  172: {
    "The Messiah would never be too proud to be a servant of Allah": "Jesus himself would never refuse to be called Allah's servant ('abd). Far from finding servitude to Allah degrading, Jesus embraced it. He never claimed divinity; he worshipped Allah. This verse uses Jesus's own humility to refute those who elevate him beyond his station.",
    "nor would the angels nearest to Allah": "Even the highest-ranking angels—those closest to Allah like Jibril—consider themselves servants of Allah. If such exalted beings don't disdain servitude to Allah, why would anyone claim a human prophet is too noble to be a servant?",
    "Those who are too proud and arrogant to worship Him will be brought before Him all together": "Regardless of their arrogance in this life, all creatures will be gathered before Allah. Pride and arrogance won't save them then. They refused to bow willingly; they will stand before Him regardless."
  },
  173: {
    "As for those who believe and do good, He will reward them in full": "Believers who back up their faith with righteous actions will receive their complete reward—nothing will be diminished or lost.",
    "and increase them out of His grace": "Beyond full reward, Allah will add extra from His bounty. This 'fadl' (grace) is a bonus—reward beyond what was strictly earned. Allah's generosity exceeds what we deserve.",
    "But those who are too proud and arrogant, He will subject them to a painful punishment": "Those who refused to worship Allah out of pride and arrogance will face severe punishment. Pride was Satan's downfall; it will be theirs too.",
    "And besides Allah they will find no protector or helper": "When the punishment comes, no one will protect them or come to their aid. The false objects of worship—whether human, angelic, or imaginary—will be useless. Only Allah could have helped them, but they rejected Him."
  },
  174: {
    "O humanity! There has come to you conclusive evidence from your Lord": "'Burhan' means clear proof, decisive evidence that leaves no room for doubt. The Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him), his message, and his miracles constitute this burhan. This proof comes from 'your Lord'—emphasizing Allah's relationship with all humanity as their Creator and Sustainer.",
    "And We have sent down to you a brilliant light": "'Noor mubin'—a clear, radiant, illuminating light. This refers to the Quran, which dispels the darkness of ignorance, superstition, and misguidance. It illuminates the path to Allah, showing clearly what is right and wrong, true and false."
  },
  175: {
    "As for those who believe in Allah and hold fast to Him": "'I'tasamu bihi'—to grip tightly, to cling firmly. This describes believers who not only believe but hold onto Allah for support, protection, and guidance. They don't let go despite difficulties.",
    "He will admit them into His mercy and grace": "Such believers will enter Allah's special mercy (rahmah) and His additional bounty (fadl). These are two layers of divine blessing—mercy that covers their sins and grace that elevates them further.",
    "and guide them to Himself through the Straight Path": "The ultimate destination is Allah Himself—His pleasure, His presence, His Paradise. The Straight Path (sirat al-mustaqeem) leads directly to Him. This guidance is continuous—He doesn't just show the path once; He guides them along it to completion."
  },
  176: {
    "They ask you ˹for a ruling, O Prophet˺. Say, \"Allah gives you a ruling regarding those who die without children or parents.\"": "This verse addresses 'kalalah'—a person who dies leaving neither children nor parents. Jabir ibn Abdullah (may Allah be pleased with him) fell ill and asked the Prophet about his inheritance since he had no children or parents, only siblings. This verse was revealed clarifying the ruling. It deals specifically with full siblings (same father and mother), distinguishing from verse 4:12 which dealt with maternal half-siblings.",
    "If a man dies childless and leaves behind a sister, she will inherit one-half of his estate": "When a man dies without children and has one full sister, she receives half of his estate. This is her fixed share (fard).",
    "whereas her brother will inherit all of her estate if she dies childless": "If the situation is reversed—a woman dies childless leaving only a brother—he inherits everything. As a male relative (asabah), he takes whatever remains after fixed shares, and if there are no other heirs, he takes all.",
    "If this person leaves behind two sisters, they together will inherit two-thirds of the estate": "If the deceased has two or more full sisters but no brothers, the sisters together receive two-thirds. This parallels the rule for daughters.",
    "But if the deceased leaves male and female siblings, a male's share will be equal to that of two females": "When there are both brothers and sisters, they share as 'asabah' (residuary heirs), with each male receiving twice the share of each female. This 2:1 ratio reflects the male's financial responsibilities in Islamic law.",
    "Allah makes ˹this˺ clear to you so you do not go astray": "These detailed inheritance laws prevent disputes, injustice, and confusion. Without clear divine guidance, people would go astray in distributing wealth, either through ignorance or favoritism.",
    "And Allah has ˹perfect˺ knowledge of all things": "Allah's knowledge encompasses all family situations, all relationships, and all financial circumstances. His laws account for every scenario with perfect justice. Surah An-Nisa ends as it began—with inheritance laws, emphasizing the importance of financial justice in family matters and the comprehensive nature of Islamic guidance."
  }
};